I love drawing, painting, animation, sculpting...anything that involves creating really. I am currently an intended Computer Science major, but depending on how things go in the coming semester, I might switch to Data Science, Operations Research, Applied Math, or something else entirely. I would also love to travel. Although I haven't been able to travel much, I plan to travel to Europe and explore every country there. In regard to myself as a roommate, I am generally easy-going. It takes a while for me to feel truly comfortable with a new person. I love myself very much and consider myself my first best friend. text: I am a very reserved and private person. I tend to keep a lot of things to myself in terms of both objects and my emotions/thoughts. I believe that there are three types of people: people who like to take life not too seriously and just have fun and enjoy, people who take life seriously and deeply and pour meaning into nearly everything, and people who are a mix of both. I would say that I lean more towards the second option. I believe that I am a very introspective and sensitive person, both emotionally and sensorily. Because of such inclinations, I do not take life lightly at all and I tend to perceive life in a deeper sense than others. I am not too outgoing, and I consider myself very introverted. I do not go outdoors too often, but when I do, I would prefer to go alone or with someone who I am deeply close with. I have a very small social group because I very much prioritize quality time, and for me, really high quality time comes only from people that are very precious to me, such as my family, or a very close friend. And because I pour my all into spending this time with such people, I do not have nor wish to expend the energy on times with others who I am not that close to. text:
As a roommate, I would consider myself to be responsible, conscientious and caring of others, clean, and relatively private. I enjoy my downtime at home and like to watch films. I am extremely conservative of energy and like to keep costs low. I do well living with others who are as considerate of me as I am of them. Similarly, my ideal roommate is someone who is also quiet and actively against disruption. I haven't had much conflict if I screen very well initially. With that said, if there was an issue, I would be very patient and likely not address it, even if it got out of hand. This is why screening is so important to me.
In a perfect universe, aside from the basics, my roommate would like to watch movies together and, if they cycle, that would be ideal to cycle together! I also would love someone who is as supportive as me, especially when it comes to academic pursuits. However, given my long history of having roommates, being close friends with my roommate is not a necessity. I've grown more open to it over time.
Like many people who are similar to me, my comfortability and openness grows over time and with consistency of a relationship. I like to set expectations/rules high, so that we don't have to retroactively address this later. I'm not as uptight as this description makes me seem.
negative_text: My history is that of inconsistent housing, and over time, I think that has shaped me to be more specific in what I look for in a roommate. text: To describe my personality using single words I believe would be an injustice. To begin, I believe anything is possible. I grew up incredibly poor, moved around a lot, and never actually had time to settle down anywhere till I arrived at high school. I saw my mom go from working 16-hour days to creating and maintaining her own successful business. I believe if you want something bad enough, and you surround yourself with people who share similar goals, you will inevitably achieve anything and everything you want. I also listen to a lot of Drake. I know, you might be wondering, what the hell does this have anything to do with this? It has a lot to do with it. I believe his music of success and possibility motivates me to achieve more every day. This man pumps album after album. single after single, and interviews after interviews, and then wakes up to do it all over again. The mindset of constantly being productive and preserving no matter the mood or situation you are in, really demonstrates how one really does have limitless potential as long as one moves and and speaks with purpose. A person with no purpose is a person with no goals or ambitions. This is not to say I don't enjoy spending time with friends and goofing off every now and then but I will never let it consume me or alter my path to success. I believe the biggest obstacle that trumps 99.99% of people off the road to success is vulnerability. Undoubtedly, being vulnerable is very hard. That I would say is a trait I have. Being vulnerable is a difficult thing. I don't know why, maybe it's all the moving or the failed friendships, but putting myself out there and really just letting myself be analyzed with no barriers or smokescreens to cover up any things I might be lacking in is my worst quality. But I believe, it's one of my strongest. Becoming too attached to something or someone will without a doubt, change your life. That is why I believe I must always keep a close but safe distance from the people I love (except my mother) because you never want to be locked down with a sinking ship (unless it's my mom, I love my mom). Anyway, I know this is pretty random, and well not to script at all but in actuality, I think it is. Using words to describe yourself is overrated, let me spiel on about random thoughts that go off in my mind and let you decide what words to use.

the anticipation is real.....

....

I never feel content with what I have. There is not a moment that goes by where I am truly happy with everything I have. I don't attribute this to my mother, or absent father, but society. We live in a society that is hyper successful, we have more millionaire's than ever before. You hop on social media and what do you see? Someone living a better, more fulfilling life. Sure I can take a break from social media and sure I shouldn't trust social media because that's not actually reality, that's merely the 1% of the 1% showing up on your feed. But I ask, that isn't reality, then why does it exist? Just something to think about. This applies to everything in my life. Work, fitness, academia, and most importantly, relationships.

I am afraid of commitment. I love my mother, and she's everything I can every ask for. What does this this have to do with commitment? Because that is the only life long commitment In which I truly feel content with. I really do believe I have the best mother in the history of mothers. However, when it comes with other people, I never have this feeling, and it scares me. I recently got out of a 5 year relationship. A lot of people around me at the time would say it was incredibly abusive, at some point I do agree with them. It was a terrible relationship, and sure we probably didn't love each other and most likely stuck it out because it was familiar to us, and in a sense, we were committed to each other, a five year contract, signed in blood and tears. In the moment, it felt like a lifetime but when it was over, felt as if it had never happened. Drunk off arguments and petty conversations that only separated us further in the hole we dug ourselves. Now that I am out, picking up a shovel and digging a new hole with someone seems the like scariest thing in this world. I have had countless opportunities to be in relationships with some woman that men would absolutely die for (and yes, I am proud about that) but then suddenly out of nowhere, I can't do it anymore. The idea of even settling down with someone ever again, scares the living crap out of me. Why? Might of been the moving around a lot when I was a kid, or maybe the idea that I could possibly find someone better. Or maybe something much deeper than all of that

Insecurities. I do not feel like that guy. Yet. I don't believe I can truly and honestly say that I can give someone all of me when I have little to nothing to give. I have this belief that women, have this intrinsic beauty to them, that men could never have. Woman are just so mesmerizing and captivating that even if a woman has nothing to her name, she can easily seduce a prince and a king to do her bidding. Of course, this isn't medieval times but the concept still applies. Woman have so much power right from birth that men will just never have. So, right now, where it stands, I don't see myself as someone who has achieved and received enough accolades to pursue and settle down with such a beautiful person. And I don't mean physical beauty, although it does matter to an extent, I mean emotional, inner beauty. Someone who can understand me as much as i wish to understand them. 

I am sure there's more but in all honestly I feel as If I have written enough and if I am being completely honest and transparent, which I is something I believe you value, right? This drop dead gorgeous girl that could only be describe using dreams and fairytales decided to sit right in front of me at the library. What a life am I right? In fact, what lives? text:
Dear future roommate,

I would say that I am an anxious extrovert. I love talking to people and gain a lot of joy and energy from it, but my anxiety and nerves make me worried that I will say the wrong thing. Therefore, I come off as shy. I would say that I am artistic - I love music and art. I play multiple instruments, and I also enjoy painting even if I am not so good at it. I am generally an optimist and enjoy looking on the bright side of things. I have trouble with this when the anxiety and nerves hit, but I want to help people (and myself) feel better so I try to be as optimistic as possible. I believe I am kind and would sacrifice a lot for others. This might just mean that I am a people pleaser though. I am talkative when I enjoy the subject. I would say I am quiet to new people. I can act confident when I need to but this is a rare occurrence. I am falsely open - I share things that I have already come to terms with and not things that I have not. I would call myself an organized mess, but I am trying to fix that. I have a partner that I care very much for, and while she is long distance, I do everything in my power to continue and strengthen that connection. I enjoy taking walks. I am not particularly fit, but I do what I can and enjoy. I need to get better about doing the dishes. I genuinely love people and I think that, for the most part, they like me. I am a bit insecure but I am trying to get over this. I think that I am hilarious. I like to think that I am a hard worker and am a bit ambitious. I tend to be thought of as smart by my friends at home, but this is everyone at Berkeley. I really just want to help people after college and be happy with my life. I don't want my career to be my entire world and I think that my friends and family are most important to me.
negative_text: I think I actually went through the positive and the negative. However, I am incredibly anxious and this can manifest as intrusive thoughts. These thoughts harm my relationships with others because that is what they tend to be about. I get stressed easily as a result and I tend to put too much on my plate. I am inconsistent - I will have a goal but have difficulty sticking to it, even if I desperately want to do so. I am a perfectionist and don't like things unless they are perfect. I tend to try and mimick those around me, creating the air of a falsely close relationship that I have not achieved. This can come across as mean. I get guilty very easy. I have body image issues and I talk about it.  I procrastinate and then get upset for how little time I have. I have a short fuse sometimes.

text:
Hello! My name is Kailiyah Hauser. I am a generally quiet and shy person who tends to keep to themselves. However, even though I am not outgoing and I am introverted, I do enjoy social connection with a small number of friends and family. I tend to have fewer deeper relationships than more casual relationships. When I spend time with people, I like to do things together that allow us to bond or get to know one another better. For instance, cooking together, or watching a show together than we can then discuss. My favorite things to do, regardless of whether they are done with others, are reading, writing, cooking, baking, eating, knitting, hiking, spending time in nature, traveling, and watching certain shows (especially cooking shows or comfort shows/movies that I have seen before). I tend to rewatch and reread things for comfort. I have anxiety that can be pretty debilitating, and I have found some things that help ground me, like Brooklyn 99 and Harry Potter. I have always had struggles with my mental health, including a history of obsessive compulsive disorder, an eating disorder, depression, and anxiety. I often experience sensory overload and will have to take time in a dark and quiet space to return to my more balanced self.

In a living space, I am clean and organized. My room always has everything put away, and disorder in my room bothers me. It makes me feel more anxious and less confident in my ability to take care of myself, so I strive to have order in my environment to aid coherence in my thoughts. I really like to have my own space so I can manage my mental health, decompress after social interaction, and keep my environment the way I like it. 

I am considerate and empathetic. I spend a lot of time thinking about others, and strive to be helpful and kind in every situation. I really value social connection, and do my best to understand the multifaceted nature of people beyond making broad assumptions. 

Some of the things that bother me include people who are inconsiderate (play their media too loud in shared spaces, lack of consideration for others' time (lateness, etc.) leave messes, etc.), driving, and people interrupting me while I'm reading.
negative_text:
I feel like I flipped these. I devoted a lot of the space in the last page to describing negative aspects of my personality (including my struggles with mental health), and I think that says a lot about my assumptions about myself. I did touch on positive aspects of my personality, like my love for deep connection and motivation to help and love others, but some other positive aspects of my personality include my genuine care for the people around me, my ability to read people really well, my love of books, my passion for food, and my willingness to take time for others. 

However, some negative characteristics that I struggle with include my propensity to jealousy and comparing myself to other people. I often struggle with feeling like I am not good enough, or feeling inferior when other people are successful. I do not like this about myself, and I constantly am doing work to try and actively counteract that mindset when it arises. 

I also have a tendency to fall into my overpowering emotions. Being empathetic to a fault and emotionally intelligent comes with extremely intense emotions, and in combination with my anxiety, this can be really debilitating. I often fall into despair about the human condition, the society in which we live, and about my own life, and I struggle to pull myself back towards positivity. 

I also struggle with anger for my family that I have not yet worked through.

text: I'm definitely quiet when you first meet me. I had a good bit of social anxiety in high school, so it still pops up every now and then when I'm meeting someone new. This means that I can come off as a bit reserved, but give me some time to warm up to you and you'll find I'm actually relatively talkative and extroverted. Every now and then I would say I tend to fall into gossip, but I try to stay drama-free and surround myself with more positivity. I have a very strong work ethic–some people would say I don't know how to stop working. When I work, I prefer to work alone especially if it's on a solo assignment, as well as in silence or with my headphones in. Even if I have my headphones in while I'm working, I don't have music on. It's more to drown out all the sounds and make sure no one is talking to me (a bit weird, I know). I'm very nervous of your first impression of me. I really don't want to be perceived as strange or rude or anything negative, which in turn might end up with me acting more strange than I might have intended. I have some tics, so you might hear me clearing my throat when I am nervous, or cracking my knuckles a bunch, or raising my eyebrows unintentionally. I love going on walks and hikes, going to the gym (but only if I'm comfortable with the people there), trying new coffee shops, and hanging out with my friends. I also love coding and working on my neuroscience research, painting, and baking.
negative_text: I tend to have a really negative mindset, caused predominantly by my competitive nature and my lack of knowing when to stop working. I always want the best for myself, but I like portraying myself as a positive person, so I never let my jealousy show when my friends get a job that I don't or get a better grade than me, even though I feel jealous deep down. I'm always the happiest when I do the best, and this could be the result of my upbringing with a tiger mom, where I would be scolded for getting anything less than an A and continuously compared to my peers despite being a hard-working student myself. I put myself down a lot, but I hide it in jokes about my appearance and personality to play off the fact that I'm upset with myself as a person. I'm easily irritable, and while I said I prefer to be drama-free, my gossip-y nature ends up with me putting myself in situations where I'm called out for sharing unnecessary secrets and speaking rudely of my own friends.

text: I am introverted, usually quite quiet, and bookish, though I do need to spend time around people to "drain my battery" that I spend recharging on my own. My attention span is quite limited: I love to read, but little sounds, activity in another room, noises and lights outside, or my own wandering mind frequently prevent me from being able to make it far in books. I am often quiet while my trains of thought "ping-pongs" around from one idea to another, giving some the impression that I come to ideas or thoughts quite randomly. Others would describe me as nice, compassionate, empathetic, and I agree with these assessments; I actively work toward empathy with others the vast majority of the time, almost constantly playing the advocate for victims and underdogs. However, i) I find this level of empathy very challenging to maintain, as it becomes very tiresome without having time to spend by myself; and ii) internally, I often find it incredibly difficult to empathize emotionally or socially with others, and am frequently acting based on what I think am empathetic person would do, rather than acting solely on empathy. I am a generally agreeable person, and aim to avoid conflict where it arises; often, I try to make the most people in a given group happy, even at the cost to the minority and myself - in this respect, I'm a very "go with the flow" kind of person. I don't need excessive plans to have a good time and enjoy myself, and in most cases a quiet day/night at home - movies, books, boardgames, walks, hikes - is my ideal way to spend time, as opposed to going out. Despite this, I am quick to annoyance, misunderstanding, and anger; however, I am also quick to reflect and try to understand if I am the one at fault for a social situation going sour. This often leads to feelings of guilt, shame, and inferiority, and sometimes further mistrust. Example: i) Person A does something that disagrees with me in a way I feel should be obvious; ii) I get mad or stressed, but stay quiet about it; iii) I quickly think of ways that I may be misinterpreting Person A's actions/intentions, and that why I would get upset is *not* obvious to them; iv) I try to move forward through life consciously thinking about how I must have been in the wrong. I am generally a little depressed and lack motivation to get started on projects, but I try to keep this from showing externally as much as possible. Finally, care deeply about genuineness and sincerity, and don't like acts and behaviors that ring hollow or are generally meaningless - one reason why I find it difficult to understand people of my own generation is, despite "woke culture" and leading with compassion, a social adherence to cynicism and falseness - the idea of "finstagram", the act of dressing "stylishly" at the cost of "comfort", and social media filters are all things that I find difficult for myself to partake in because, while I understand why these and other things are done, they don't make intuitive sense to me, so maybe that means my personality is a bit socially conservative, though my political and financial ideology is incredibly liberal.
negative_text: I am slow to change, and I certainly don't put in as much effort into things - everything from work, to school, to friend-relationship maintenance, and even personal interests/passions/hobbies - as I could (and as I often think, as I should). I feel a lot of imposter syndrome as a human being living in our social society; I try to be as empathetic as possible, but often find myself hugely lacking in my ability to empathize. I can be a bit of a germ-a-phobe and am generally mistrustful of others' senses of cleanliness; on the opposite side of things, I'm generally not a neat person, and don't often leave things in the same spot as when I found them. I try to actively correct for this, though. What else? I'm easy to "shut-down" at the first sign that I've offended someone or made someone feel uncomfortable, which in many cases only leads to others feeling bad that they've made me feel bad which (you guessed it) leads to more feeling bad on my part. I'm easy to start spiraling into self-loathing when I've made others upset, or even spiralling just in an existential way. However, I've always been able to pick myself up out of those darker places.

text: I am a pretty creative and social person, I love to spend time with friends, and I am always down to do whatever people want to do. I like watching movies, listening to music, going to the beach, running, swimming, and going for coffee and talking about things like politics, philosophy and psychology. I also like watching tennis. I sometimes get more stressed out than necessary, although I won't put that on other people and prefer to move through stress on my own, because I notice I can get frustrated and say things that I don't mean when I am too stressed to other people. However, I am very open with most other things with other people, I overshare a lot and will talk about anything. I am always here if others want to talk to me about their problems or get advice from me. I enjoy cooking, although I like eating more and am always ready to go out for a meal(if I have money). I like to debate and argue about ideas when I get closer to people and know that they won't be offended, but I tend to get super into ideas and looking for the truth of things. negative_text: I did mention that I am messy and disorganised in the other writing assignment, but I didn't go into much detail. I also swear a lot, which some people consider to be negative, and have a scathing sense of humour with those I am close to that I feel can sometimes come off as harsh. I think I have a little bit of a quick temper, however I never hold a grudge and get over my annoyance at others pretty quickly. I can be overly judgemental sometimes, especially of men which I think is a little unfair, but I suppose it is because I perceive danger from them more. I have a tendency for stress and anxiety as I mentioned before, and have had panic attacks in the past, which often tend to be triggered by traveling, which I have to do a lot because my family is in England and on the east and west coast of the US.

text: I tend to be a very social person in the sense that I feel comfortable around people and tend to feel more negative emotions when alone. I like talking to people and I also feel more comfortable sitting in silence with others than alone. I enjoy having both deep connections with others and a wide social network of friends and acquaintances. At the same time, I highly value alone time because it pushes me out of my comfort zone and I am often at my most productive and healthy in terms of routine when alone. I much prefer to have my own room because of the freedom it gives me to structure my time and also to relax and let go of the social energy I carry with me most of the time. In general, I would say I am a very open person–I consider new ideas and change my mind in light of new information. However, sometimes I still bristle when faced with things that conflict with strongly held beliefs and expectations. I am not a very conscientious person–I tend to be forgetful and make silly mistakes. However, I tend to do well in school because I am motivated to succeed and when I do focus I can be very productive. As I mentioned previously, I am fairly extroverted. However, I do also sometimes feel awkward and self-conscious when interacting with others. I would say I am a pretty nice, kind, and empathetic person when it comes to my intentions. I care a lot about not hurting people's feelings and trying to behave ethically. I also make an effort to approach people with positive energy. However, sometimes stress and/or a lack of conscientiousness lead me to behave in a way that comes off as mean or at least emotionally unaware. I believe I can be very neurotic–I have struggled with anxiety and depression off and on throughout my life and to this day one small thing can put me in a negative state of mind which becomes hard to escape. However, others have also told me that I handle problems well and tend to have a very positive and mature outlook on life. I think I have been able to moderate my neuroticism with an intentionally positive outlook at times.
negative_text: I didn't touch on a lot of things in the previous section. There are good things, like my intellectual curiosity and drive to help others and engage in public service, which I believe are important parts of who I am. But there are also bad things that I didn't touch on. I can be a very jealous person, and sometimes the success of others makes me feel bad when it should make me feel good. Sometimes I resent other people who are close to me as a product of my own internal pain–I resent them when I perceive them as being better than me. I got bullied a lot as a kid and I guess I have a "chip on my shoulder." I still feel a need sometimes to prove myself in some way—as the most masculine person in the room? The smartest? The most successful? The worst person to pick a fight with? It changes but I do believe that I often have an unhealthy focus on how others perceive me and it can lead me to behave in negative ways. Ultimately, I think this mindset stems from a need to prove to myself that I am strong, successful, "masculine"–basically the opposite of the kid who got bullied. I would like to be more comfortable in being different from other people and in not fitting the molds that society tells us are cool or desirable.

text: I am an outgoing and social introvert; I enjoy meeting new people, making friends and having new experiences, but I recharge in a solitary and quiet way. I am charismatic, funny, and intelligent. I am kind to others. I am disciplined and focus on my goals and do everything I can to achieve them. I am empathetic and self-aware, almost to a fault. I often feel that I feel too much, and am highly susceptible to this. I also often feel anxious. Because of my self-awareness, I am able to try and conceptualize how others feel and think of me, and this often leads to critical assessment of myself. Therefore, I often hold myself back from expressing parts of myself, and often, large parts of myself remain unexpressed. This leads to a lot of feelings of displeasure and dissonance inside myself. I am kind, but do not always extend that kindness to myself. I am creative, I like to express myself through my creative hobbies. I am able to lighten the mood in most situations. I am fun-loving, but also work hard to complete what is expected of me. I often feel self-conscious and feel I can be a bit high-strung when stressed or feeling self-conscious. I want to feel better about myself and the things I do, which leads me to work hard in my life. I treat others with respect, care, and grace. I struggle to do the same with myself. I have a strong moral compass, and am able to differentiate right from wrong. Because of my self-awareness and empathy, when I do do something I find morally wrong, I quickly feel guilt and shame, especially after placing myself in the perspective of the other person. I find myself always wanting to improve from the person I am now. Sometimes this causes me to not enjoy the present moment, or love and appreciate who I am now. I do not have this same attitude with others, instead loving and accepting them as they are most of the time.
negative_text: I am not sure what negative aspects I left out that I did not already mention. I did try to mention as much as possible. However, I do often judge myself, and this in turn does lead me to also judge others at times, although, the judgment I pass on others is not as severe as what I turn upon myself. This can make me seem self-deprecating to others, and give other people a worsened or lowered perception of who I am. I often find myself fearing that others will not like me, and so will not give them the opportunity to make that decision for themselves, because I repress or silence myself. This especially comes off in front of new people. Sometimes, I get so stuck in my own head and imagination of how others see and think of me, that I am unable to express myself or be involved in social interactions. This is a challenge I have faced for my entire life, and one I am constantly pushing against and working on in my own life. I am slow to make judgments about others, but quick to do so with myself. I am often unable to forgive myself for things that were either out of my control, or that have happened in the past and are now unchangeable. I feel a high sense of responsibility, to the point where I worry that it can be overbearing at times. I overthink to the point of stressing myself out.

text: I am a type of person who likes things a certain way. Usually, I need my lifestyle structured with my own space being untouched with the only exception of myself. text: I am an introvert. That's the adjective that always comes to mind first when I'm asked to describe myself. I am more shy than outgoing, which can often come across as just being quiet. I like spending time alone and with other people, but if I have been doing one of those more than the other, I start to notice that I miss either solitude or having company. I am very careful to be quiet and unobtrusive, especially in the context of having roommates. I very rarely listen to music or play things without headphones, even if I am home alone. A lot of my hobbies involve working on my own, most of them are also quiet if not totally silent. If I am drawing or painting or sometimes reading, I can stay focused on that for hours without noticing that time is passing. I tend to see things in black and white terms, so I have to consciously exert effort to see things in a more nuanced way. As I'm writing this, I can't stop looking down at the timer counting down right below the box. I can be very talkative if I am comfortable with someone, often taking a long time to get to the point, if I ever get to it. I try really hard to not interrupt people, I used to do it a lot, and until it was pointed out to me, I didn't notice. I am very pessimistic, I've been cynical even since I was little. I am superstitious in a lot of ways, but I am also scornful of myself for believing in things like jinxes and bad luck and astrology, even though they're fairly harmless. I am very conscious of myself and worry about the way I'm coming across, I worry a lot about being irritating or seeming unkind. My neutral face and stance make me seem alternatively angry or sad, so I don't think I'm very approachable, and I used to hate that. If I catch myself thinking in a way that's very judgmental or mean or negative, I try to reframe it in a more positive light, since my automatic tendency is to assume the worst. I draw every day, and I have to remind myself that if I am enjoying something, it is worthwhile.
negative_text: I am not super reliable. I am bad at texting back or responding to emails in a timely manner. I need constant reassurance. I am both always convinced that I am right and I know best but also completely sure that I am stupid and everyone else knows things that I don't. I push people away before they can choose to leave me first. I have an obsessive need to control. I am good at bringing the tone or mood in a room down to a very depressing place. I make self deprecating jokes and dark humor at my own expense that makes people uncomfortable before I can annoy them just by being myself. I intellectualize my emotions so I don't have to experience them. I do not think I am a nice person. I don't know if I'm a good person, but it's never been all that concerning to me that I might not be good. I think I am more like my father, and I hate that. I project expectations onto other people that aren't fair to them. I have no idea what I'm really like, even writing this I feel like I'm making it up or lying somehow. I wallow in negativity and ignore hope and help in favor of staying in the bad place I'm in. I never shut up, I have to be told to stop talking or interrupting in order for my brain to finally stop spitting out words. I use my mental illnesses as a crutch and as excuses for why I'm not happy or better. I don't think I'll ever be happy, and I don't try to be.

text: Hi there! I don't think we're supposed to put our names here, but if we were this is the part where I'd do that. I'd describe myself as someone who is very compassionate, is always conscientious of how others might be feeling (I like to make sure everyone feels included in the conversation and, more generally, comfortable), and who values above all else authenticity and honesty. I am arguably overly-trusting, which is a good and a bad thing at times; I am very sociable, love good conversation, and especially enjoy meeting new people. In this way, I'd say I'm very gregarious and open to new things- adventurous. However, I am also more often than not very inquisitive about the world around me and, even moreso, curious about what this life holds for me and why things, including personality, are the way they are. I am fascinated and deeply appreciative of all of our unique individual differences which, I feel, actually connect us in the sense that while we have such differences in traits, for example, these differences merely contribute to a difference in the way we see the world and life more generally- our perception(s) of our life situation(s). When making friends or meeting new people more broadly, I always seek to learn from others, as I believe everyone to be my superior in at least one area- not necessarily intellectually, but in at least one area of life such as spirituality, etc. Ultimately, I'd describe myself as someone who is just along for the ride of life, who has no expectations for life, and who is contented by whatever I have, am given, or is thrown my way; for this reason, I am also highly resilient. Anyway, that's a little about me! Hope this is a helpful introduction. :)
negative_text: Although I have a generally positive view of the world, at times I can become a bit cynical and sad. It is, however, extremely difficult for me to reach this negative state: I am a through-and-through optimist who has God in my life, who gives me such purpose and meaning each and every day! Even with this optimistic view of life, though, I sometimes become negative when I feel that I'm getting nothing done, especially after I've been working on it for a long time (frustration would be the word to best describe this I think). I am also very slow to process things, which is not necessarily a bad thing, since it helps me really think things through, and has helped foster a patience and reverence towards myself and, more specially, towards moving at my own pace. I tend to take a long time on things, as mentioned earlier, in large part because I am a perfectionist; I would also consider myself a little OCD, in that I like things neat and tidy, including my own handwriting (in fact, in high school I used to rewrite a word completely if it wasn't "pretty" or "perfect" enough for my standards- I was literally called the "human typewriter" for my then-perfect handwriting. This is not as true to this day since I am now perfectly fine with messy handwriting, but just thought I'd mention it for additional context).

text: Good listener, empathetic, respectful, cute, and open-minded; those adjectives I have heard associated with my personality when someone asks what type of person I am to those who have interacted with me. The combination of these five describes how I typically identify with and try to portray. People feel at ease when they talk to me about "deep" subjects because I become invested in what they are communicating to me which leads me to ask questions. By doing this, I achieve people for people to feel listened to because that is how I would like to be treated as well. This leads me to the next point: empathy. Sometimes I don't know if it is a quality or or curse because I am able to put myself in other people's shoes to the point where I literally feel the problem to be my own problem. However, this becomes a blessing when it's an achievement because I feel the same amount of joy for them as they do for the achievement. I think that people think I am cute because it is a combination of shyness, empathy, and respect that they associate with the concept of cuteness (my big doe eyes may also be a factor.) Lastly, while I do have extremely strong values, I truly believe that open-mindedness is a key to getting along with most people regardless of whether they have contrasting perspectives about life. Really understanding what it is that people believe and why they are that way can lead to having a more harmonious life in theory. Nevertheless, in the past couple of years, my radicalization of these ideals has led me to be more selective of the people that I hang out with and therefore to create an image of myself to be more distant or shy than the average extrovert, but more social than an introvert.
negative_text: As I mentioned before, I have developed a stronger position on being more open-minded, respectful, empathetic, and a better listener. However, this has caused me to wander about the limits and drawbacks of being too open-minded. Does being too open-minded mean that because you understand and agree with each point you hear, you are unstable or have "weak" values? This has led me to feel more lonely at times and distant to people.

text:
I'm an outgoing and sociable individual who thrives on human connections. The prospect of moving in with a new roommate for the upcoming academic year fills me with excitement and anticipation. As an extrovert, I genuinely enjoy engaging in conversations and building meaningful relationships with others. I find great joy in getting to know people from diverse backgrounds and discovering the unique experiences and perspectives they bring to the table. So, rest assured, I'll be more than happy to strike up conversations and create a comfortable, friendly atmosphere in our shared living space.
When it comes to my favorite activities, I have a couple of passions that bring me immense happiness. One of them is playing tennis. I find the sport to be not only physically invigorating but also mentally stimulating. The feeling of stepping onto the court, the satisfying sound of the racket hitting the ball, and the thrill of a well-executed shot make tennis a source of pure joy for me. Additionally, golf is another sport that I enjoy. There's something serene about being out on the green, surrounded by nature, and challenging myself to improve my swing and accuracy.
In my leisure time, you'll often find me engrossed in watching Chinese dramas. I have developed a deep appreciation for the captivating storytelling and rich cultural elements these dramas offer. They transport me to different worlds, allowing me to immerse myself in compelling narratives and explore the beauty of Chinese culture. If you're interested, I'd be more than happy to introduce you to some of my favorite series and share the excitement of discovering new stories together.
Beyond my interests and hobbies, my overarching life goal revolves around maintaining a healthy and balanced well-being. I firmly believe that taking care of oneself is crucial for personal growth and happiness. Whether it's through regular exercise, mindful practices, or nourishing my mind with books and knowledge, I strive to prioritize my physical, mental, and emotional health. By doing so, I hope to cultivate a harmonious and fulfilling lifestyle that positively impacts those around me.
I hope this extended description provides a clearer understanding of who I am as a person and what I value. I'm genuinely looking forward to embarking on this new living experience with you, creating lasting memories, and fostering a supportive and enjoyable living environment.
negative_text:
When it comes to describing some of the less positive aspects of my personality or the feelings I experience, there are several aspects worth mentioning. Firstly, I have a tendency to engage in procrastination when it comes to completing my homework or tasks. Despite knowing the importance of timely action, I often find myself delaying the work, which can lead to increased stress and pressure as deadlines approach.
Additionally, I consider myself to be quite sensitive, and this sensitivity can manifest in various ways. For instance, I can feel uncomfortable or uneasy in environments that are dirty or excessively cold. These conditions have a significant impact on my mood and overall sense of well-being, often prompting me to seek cleanliness and warmth as a means of creating a more comfortable space for myself.
Moreover, overthinking is another characteristic that I struggle with. I have a tendency to excessively analyze situations, events, and conversations, often dwelling on negative outcomes or potential problems. This habit of overthinking can be mentally exhausting and can hinder my ability to make decisions confidently, as I become entangled in a web of uncertainties and doubts.
Furthermore, I find it challenging to let go of things, whether it's past mistakes, regrets, or possessions. This difficulty in letting go can create emotional baggage, preventing me from fully embracing the present moment and moving forward in a more positive and productive way. It takes considerable effort and self-reflection for me to release attachments and allow myself the freedom to grow and evolve.
In addition to that, I tend to exhibit perfectionistic tendencies. I have a strong desire for things to be in order and to meet high standards of excellence. This pursuit of perfection can be both a blessing and a curse, as it drives me to strive for excellence but also creates a constant feeling of dissatisfaction and restlessness. It can even affect my ability to relax and sleep when things are not in their desired place or state.
Lastly, impatience is another aspect of my personality that I wrestle with. When faced with delays, setbacks, or situations that don't align with my expectations, I can become easily frustrated and agitated. This impatience often stems from a deep desire for efficiency and progress, but it can sometimes hinder my ability to remain calm and composed in challenging circumstances.
Overall, acknowledging and addressing these negative aspects of my personality and feelings is essential for personal growth and self-improvement. By recognizing these tendencies, I can work towards developing coping strategies and adopting a more balanced and positive approach to life's challenges.

text:
I think the best way to describe myself is to think about how my friends would describe me. In general, I'm known to be quite determined, genuine, honest, and empathetic. I'm a loyal friend and apparently a good listener/advice-giver. I am reliable, as some of my friends this summer have said I give off "big sister energy," which likely comes from the fact that I am responsible with myself, with the people I choose to spend time with, and anticipate the needs of others which makes it seems like I always know what to do or what to say. 

I think there are different scenarios when you first meet me. Sometimes I can come off as quite reserved and private, and other times I'm the first one to strike the conversation. I like to protect my time and have self care days, but also enjoy spontaneously hanging out with friends or making plans to do some sort of activity in advance. I'd say I'm a pretty balanced and predictable person based on the way I treat my friends and family. 

I am hardworking. I take my academics and career goals quite seriously, but have gotten a lot better at not giving myself too much pressure. I've learned to trust myself with the years of experiences I've had to learn my strengths and weaknesses. As such, I feel like I am also always looking out for the the best interests of others when making decisions or handling conflict. I'd say I used to have a lot of discipline in things regarding my goals, health, and wellbeing, but I've been less strict and punitive about it in the past year.

In terms of things I like to do, I like being active. I try to exercise whenever I have the energy, play volleyball whenever I'm free, and try to go on little hikes or walks with my friends. I think my friends are a core factor in what I choose to do or spend my time; company matters a lot to me, especially when I'm trying or experiencing something new. 

I think that I'm a more optimistic person now. Most days I am relatively happy, and try not to let negative emotions influence how I interact with others. I do get into slumps sometimes, but I always look forward to when those days are over.
negative_text:

I don't think it affects me as much now, but definitely did a lot of my childhood and teenage years. Either I've gotten better at dealing with it, or its been repressed (which I will have to admit does come out sometimes during stressful times like exams or job recruiting).

I also think I can be unapproachable at times. Upon meeting someone for the first time, or being in a new situation where I potentially feel insecure or don't trust a person, I can come off as quiet and standoff-ish. It's much harder for me to open up in those situations, and likely people won't think I'm relatable or necessarily fun and easy to talk to. My mom used to describe me as a porcupine, where, if you get to close or if I feel threatened, my quills will spike out. 

On the same vein, I can seem very nonchalant to people who are not as close to me. I'm less willing to drop what I'm doing to help that person unless I truly mean it. Some people can't take this brute honesty and I try to distance myself in an appropriate way so that it doesn't become offensive.

text: Each individual has a different form of personality that is able to relate or differ from one person to another. At the end of the day, we each have our own unique qualities and traits that makeup who we are. When it comes to describing my own personality, I would say that I have more positive characteristics than negative ones. I am a very outgoing individual who loves to get involved in different conversations and activities. I am always open to learning about new topics and engaging in new adventures to expand my knowledge and expand the variety of experiences I have gone through. I would like to say that I am an extrovert who can engage in conversations with whoever I come across and I am someone who enjoys engaging in these conversations because it allows me to connect with new people and understand them in different ways. I can crack a funny joke or make a compliment when I meet someone new in order to create an atmosphere of comfortableness and openness between me and the other individual. I am also someone who truly enjoys being out of my comfort zone. I was born and raised in Los Angeles, California and I have lived a pretty comfortable life for the past eighteen years. As soon as I turned nineteen, I knew it was time to start being more independent and moving on with my life. Leaving my family, my job, my friends, and my life back home was very hard to do, but I am glad to be out of my comfort zone and trying new things every day. Meeting a new individual and becoming roommates with them is something that I have truly enjoyed so far. You have no idea who these people are and they have no idea who you are, it is the ability to get a fresh start and be the person you have always wanted to be. Currently, I live with three other roommates and I am confident to say that we have built a very special and strong connection so far. We took the time to get to know each other and we all shared our backgrounds in order to understand each other much better. My roommates have been able to view my personality as someone who is interesting, caring, loyal, open, and as someone who has the ability to engage and create deep conversations that could last hours. Just last night, we had an intense conversation until three in the morning speaking about our lives and what we want to do in the future. I got to introduce them to my friends back home via FaceTime and it was a very wonderful experience, and definitely a core memory. I also got to introduce them to my favorite sports, such as water polo and swimming. I am also a lifeguard, and I brought a rescue tube from my job back home to put in my dorm. My roommates were confused and asking about what it was, so it was very fun to explain to them what it is used for and my experience as a lifeguard.
negative_text: We all have our good sides and our bad sides, and for some people, it takes a long time to come to terms with what makes them hold these negative qualities. I tend to overthink the smallest things which cause me to ruin my entire day just by thinking about something small or having no importance at all. This is a negative characteristic I have because when I am overthinking something, my entire mood and attitude begin to change since it is the only thought I am having in my brain. It is very hard to overcome this sort of negative behavior, but it also allows me to understand that it is a human emotion that I can deal with and it allows me to be conscious about what is going on and why I am overthinking a certain topic. Instead of feeling bad about myself for it, I like to take it as a learning experience and I allow myself to grow and understand the situation from a better and different perspective. text: Over recent years I have found that I have changed dramatically from who I used to be. In grade school I was always very shy, had many friends but kept to myself for the most part, I did not like being the center of attention as it made me socially anxious. Fast forward to present day I am more socially anxious than ever (I had to start going to therapy which was a huge step for me) but despite this I have found that I don't let my anxiety stop me from achieving goals of mine, which requires a lot of social engagement. Although I can be friendly to others I find that my anxiety makes me come across as rude sometimes. For example, when I am in a large setting and there are many unfamiliar faces I don't engage as much as I should with these people I am surrounded with. I am very fond of classic rock music, it can be very loud and obnoxious but it surprisingly calms my anxiety. Most people my age aren't familiar with the bands and artists I listen to, therefore I have been told that I am different than most people, some people find my taste in music unique while others find it peculiar. Another activity that calms my anxiety, besides music, is painting. I enjoy using acrylic paint on my free time. How do people perceive me? Well based on interactions with friends and family I am told that I can be very conscientious. I think my anxiety has made me this way. Furthermore I can also be very impulsive in the sense that something that crosses my mind, like stopping what I am doing and running to a tattoo shop to get my inner lip tattooed (this is a true story). text: I am someone who is pretty impulsive. I cannot stick to a self-made schedule to save my life so I do my work as my motivation comes and goes. Despite this, I am a very calm person. I take situations as they come and am generally great in a crisis (which I know from experience). This doesn't mean that I do not worry about all the little things - be it whether my sister is doing ok in the room next door, whether I have fed the dog this morning, or if my dad is enjoying his day/night back home in Germany. I laugh easily, come to conclusions readily (although I often come to the opposite conclusion some while later, and may even switch back once more). text: I'd say my personality is quite vivacious. I am a person who is very easily-excitable and has an over-the-top reaction to many things. This coincides with the fact that I'd say Im pretty opinionated. Once I am comfortable with a person I have a hard time shutting my mouth, even when I probably should, and people will always know what is on my mind, but again, this is only if I am comfortable with the person and know them well. I'd say my outspokenness also makes me a very anxious person with people I do not know well. I know I have a hard time shutting my mouth once im open with a person, so I am extremely cautious with who and what I open up about at first. I have a really hard time introducing myself and making new friends, but if someone does decide to speak to me and try to crack my shell I give in really easily. I love to talk, I just hate the judgement that comes with it- if that makes sense. Over time I have kind of grown to hate how much I speak as often I will walk away from a conversation hating every word I ever spoke and it will indeed haunt me for the rest of my week. I think my own hatred for my voice ties in with why I am so enthusiastic and almost theatrical when I talk. Since I understand how traumatizing speaking can be I always try my best to be very open and receptive of others peoples words so they hopefully walk away with no regrets and are happy that they chose to open up to me. Some other aspects of my personality could be that I am very clumsy and forgetful. I often trip over things, bump into tables, accidentally knock over objects, you get the jist. My forgetfulness is not much better, for example today I had to drive back to the Bay Area from Chico and though I thought I packed everything, 5 minutes into my car ride I got a call from my boyfriend saying I forgot my laptop which was probably the most important thing for me to have remembered. Im not sure if being a bit of a mental mess is considered a personality trait, but it is an aspect of myself that people close to me seem to really notice and look out for now. Some other notable things about my personality could also be that I've been told I have a quick-wit. I am very fast to make a joke or comment back at people and love to word my sentences in odd ways. I think this is because my brain works at 600mph and connections come to me very quickly once I am spoken to, again this all ties back to thinking I am a vivacious person because there is never a lack of words or reactions when one is speaking to me. I may never spark the conversation, but I am also never the one to end it either.
negative_text: Oh boy where do I start. As I touched on in the last question, I never shut up, and I am also very anxious. These two are ingredients for a lovely self-hating cocktail because though I would like to talk and walk away from the interaction happy, I tend to walk away wanting to bury myself in a hole and never come out. This is frustrating for the people I am closest to because they have to deal with me constantly looking at myself in a pessimistic way, and obviously, that is not very healthy. I pity my boyfriend because no mater how hard I try to restrict myself from telling him my negative thoughts, I simply can't help but unleash my load of bad news and thoughts to him. I fear often that this makes me draining to be around, he says he loves to hear me talk, even about the bad stuff, but my self doubt can't help but tell me this i snot true. I also feel bad for my best-friend at times because if I ever speak to her about my negative thoughts (whether it be about me appearance or personality) I fear that she may start looking at herself in a negative way, or searching for what my flaws are within her self. I know comparison is something that comes naturally to women so I never want my words to impose on how she views herself but I also know that cant be helped. Finally, this brings me to the point where I believe my own self-hatred can make me judgemental of others which is also something I am greatly ashamed of. Since I am so hyper-aware of my flaws sometimes I will meet other people and search to see if they too have these flaws. I absolutely hate this about myself and try my very best to train my brain to not think that way, but sometimes I slip up and catch my thoughts being extremely bitchy and I wish I could just love myself more so I can see more of the best in other people and improve my relationship with those I love the most. I guess this can all be summed up to my self-esteem is shit and it makes me unhealthy to be around at times.

text:
I would describe my personality as adventurous & organized.
I tend to love to explore and have an interest to learn more about different cultures, people, cuisines, places, activities, and more. This stems from a genuine curiosity for others. From this, I also tend to be an obsessive person, fully exploring and diving into different things. An example is a love for cooking foods from different cultures & trying and reviewing foods from several varied restaurants. I also like to listen to many types of music, thus I have over 100 playlists in my Spotify! I've also watched over 2000 episodes of Japanese animes and over 100 horror movies of many different languages. Once I find enjoyment in an activity, I tend to go all in.

I am also an exceptionally organized person. I love to create schedules, itineraries, plan trips/vacations. There is nothing more satisfying than fully and clearly planning out my visions for the future and then reaping the fruits of my labor. Being adventurous while being organized gives me a true sense of satisfaction and helps me feel autonomous and in control of my life and my actions.

I am an obsessive person, and I like to have full autonomy over group projects, competitions, my relationships, etc. It can be suffocating and sometimes a bit extreme. I also have anxiety when things don't unfold in a predictable manner or don't go my way. I struggle sometimes with "going with the flow" and prefer having plans and structure. I have come to realize that many positive experiences come from true spontaneity, thus I hope to improve this aspect about myself.

text: The way that I would describe my personality is very outgoing and talkative. I love spending time with people and getting to know different kinds of personalities. I would say that I get a bit intimidated when people are on the extremely extroverted side and love parties, big crowds and a lot of people.
negative_text: I can be very lazy and not finish tasks. I am very motivated to start new tasks and take risks, but I have a hard time completing projects. I can make empty promises and not fulfill them, which makes me feel terrible and more unmotivated. I struggle with staying consistent and striking a balance between work and play. I also struggle with implementing discipline and routine and go in cycles of having a perfect schedule to a complete mess.

text: My personality is harmonious with most people, meaning I don't find it too hard to get along with others. It's not necessarily that I'm a pushover or a people pleaser, rather I am friendly and social, as well as conscientious. I can keep a conversation going and maintain eye contact but I am aware if a person is uncomfortable or wants to stop talking or if a person in the group hasn't been able to share yet (which I try to ask them a question directly to allow the focus to shift). I can also be a cynical person, however, I keep most of these thoughts to myself as I don't think they need to be said out loud unless the situation presents itself. I am quite level-headed, more logical thinking than emotional/feeling when I make decisions. I'm both a homebody and down for an adventure outdoors (overall open to experiences) as I'd love to just have a day in where we bake or watch a movie, but also maybe a day where we go for a hike or see where life takes us in SF. I am a bit of a germaphobe, so you'll catch me wiping the counters or sweeping often (it may tie into slight perfectionism as well). As outgoing as I am, I am not a very loud person and enjoy the quiet, especially at night. I overthink, stress, and worry a lot (mainly about my life and future) so I might complain about stress headaches, but I assure you I'm fine and trying to stress less!
negative_text: I think I included my main two negative personality aspects (cynicism and overthinking) but I can go more in-depth as I did for the positive traits. My cynicism relates to my past experiences and traumas as I have learned how to cope over time (not always in a healthy way) and figure out how to protect my feelings and others' feelings. I can be manipulative, I don't think it's hard to get people to agree with my idea by making them believe it was their idea. In the past, it was easy to manipulate a situation to try and get my friends to just skip the drama and see the right choice in a situation (ie: yes break up with your boyfriend, who clearly doesn't love you, instead of prolonging it and making your life more miserable). but I don't do it much anymore because it made me feel like I was playing "God" when people need to learn on their own. I have anger issues and repress my emotions a lot, this won't really create any problems as I am good at not having outbursts, but it does affect things like my level of patience. When I overthink or stress, it can honestly cause a little existential crisis where I feel the need to plan out my life for the next 10 years (which obviously isn't possible but I try anyways). I'll believe I'm good for nothing and have barely made it far for some weird, obscure reason instead of seeing that I did work hard and continue to work hard for my goals.

text: I am a hardworking, compassionate, extroverted and openminded person. I care a lot about having a balance in my life between academics, work, family, friends, and personal self care. I feel best when I get to be helpful and bring some joy to someone during the day, whether that be for a stranger, the kids that I work with, or my friends/family. I can be a bit spacey, disorganized, and easily distracted, especially when I am having a burst of energy or have too much on my plate. Even though my life can feel a little chaotic, I still manage to take strides towards my educational and personal goals. When I have free time between work and class, I listen to music, go on runs, play music and go to a coffee shops. Most of the time, I feel confident and secure in my abilities, my self, and the path that I am on. I tend to have an optimism in life that things are happening for a reason and I am where I need to be.
negative_text: I think that the prior prompt lended itself to writing more positive things about self (because of the hypothetical roommate reading it). If I were being honest, I believe all of those things that I wrote to be true and I am in a good mood as I am writing, so it doesn't feel like a facade. That being said, I didn't talk about the fact that I had to work through multiple addictions and join a twelve step program in order to get to the place that I am now. While I no longer am in active addiction, I still have selfish thoughts, impulsive tendencies, and black and white thinking. I can become dependent on people or things to supply me with self worth if I slack on doing the self care in my life in order to feel happily and usefully whole. In those moments when I stop doing the right things in my life, I begin feeling anxious and overwhelmed by people and my responsibilities.

text:
Nice, caring, & friendly. Always try and be considerate of others and show empathy in any given situation. Understand that people act in certain ways for reasons unknown to me, so I always try to be careful with how I treat and judge others. 

Outgoing, when it comes to people I like and know. Enjoy spending time with friends and family, but not too rowdy. Love love love all pets and animals.

Also enjoy spending time alone and decompressing in solitude. Am introverted when I want to and extroverted around known friends & family. 

Deeply enjoy nature and spending time outdoors. 

Slightly obsessive and annoying about keeping everything clean and neat. Like some things to be done in certain ways, but can still appreciate when effort is shown. 

Tries hard to focus on school and studies, but gets distracted very easily. Loves being lazy, even though I can acknowledge it's not productive. 

Gets mad, upset, and annoyed when having to repeat self. If feeling annoyed, I will warn you before I get mad, and then explode if you continue to upset me. 

Very closed off and private until I decide I can trust you. But I can assure you that you can trust me. Believe that trust is incredibly important and always try to act in such a way, even if the same amount of trust is not returned.
negative_text:
Previously wrote about negative things. Some more negative characteristics below. 

Stubborn. Once I get an idea in my head it is very hard to change it. 

Blunt, sometimes to a fault. I'll tell you how it is, but not ever with the intention of causing any harm. However, sometimes this can deeply hurt people. 

Often grumpy for stupid reasons. This can be solved with food, sleep, sunshine, or pets.

text: I am a very outgoing person. I like my quiet time, but I very much enjoy socializing and getting to know other people and their social circles. I have very strong feelings and find it hard to suppress them, so it is very easy to read what I am feeling and/or thinking. I like to workout, learn, and most of all spend time in my faith. I love health and fitness, meal prepping, running, lifting weights, and yoga/restorative workouts. I would say I am pretty chill; however, I can be quite irritable at times, especially with my parental figures. Although I am very fond of them and love them a lot, they can be too much for me to bear at times, especially since I like peace and quiet. I am very close to my faith and enjoy spending time with the saints and friends socializing.
negative_text: Like I said, I am quiet irritably. I am trying to get better at communicating this, but I am still learning. I can be lazy too when I am tired, and in the context of someone living with someone, I am very messy. I am not mean, but I can be cold in an attempt to not say anything mean. text: I am a somewhat outgoing person. I tend to be talkative and humorous when I am with a group of friends who I am familiar with. I am also the type of person that we feel guilty very easily, I often worry about whether the thing I did would hurt others' feelings.
negative_text: I am the type of person who likes joking and talking in a direct way. Although some people will think I am humorous, sometimes the way I talk still hurts people's feelings. Moreover, I often overthink a simple thing which will make myself feel nervous and stressed easily.

text:
I'm Francesca, and my major personality traits are kindness, compassion, and positivity. These characteristics allows me to care strongly about others, especially my friends and family, and support them. I always try to look at the bright side of events and transmit this mindset to others as it's helped me being happier and more successful. 
I've always found it interesting to analyze people's thoughts and behaviors, which has driven me to studying psychology. I'm truly passionate about the subject, therefore I love reading psychology-related books and taking psychology courses. I also care about health and wellness a lot, so I like practicing sports and meditating regularly. I'm introverted so I tend to do these activities alone, but I never mind having a friend tagging along! In fact, while I enjoy my alone time, I strongly value having a sense of connection with others. I love having deep conversations, both about emotions and experiences, and about life and the world! I might look reserved and quiet, but I'm always excited to have conversation with people as I think that we can always learn something from anyone. I appreciate you for reading this.
negative_text: I am very organized, which has mostly served me well in life. However, this trait sometimes takes over me and my desire to help others. While being highly organized is a good thing for me, it might not be the same for my friends or family. For this reason, they may find me annoying for wanting to plan things in detail and wishing they do the same! Additionally, being so meticulous and exigent makes me wish to always reach perfection, which is not realistic, thus sometimes slows me down or stresses me out.

text: I would describe my personality as a bubbly, friendly, considerate, empathetic, generous type of person. I think I would say I am bubbly because I smile and laugh very easily. It does not take much to make me smile whether it is a small joke someone says or says something that makes my day. I think this is a good trait that I have because a little smile can make someone else's day and I can also say that I am content with my life. The words I used to describe myself a lot is being generous and considerate. I know that everyone has a story behind them and that there are always going to be struggles in their lives. Even if I may not have a similar problem as the person surrounding me, I would try to help them, give advice, try to distract them from the issue going on in their life, or just try to comfort them in a way that would help them. I would also say that I am easygoing because even if I have a routine in my daily life, I am not strict with it. I am pretty flexible with it so I am always willing to try new things and meeting new people which has been a big trait that has been nice to have while coming to Berkeley. Other words to describe me is very hardworking. I try to do the best on everything I do because sometimes we only have one shot to complete it or fulfill it. I do not want to put in minimum effort and do poorly as I set expectations for myself. I want my parents to be proud of all the work I do and I also want to be proud of my work so I would put in as much effort as I can give myself to complete a task. I try to motivate myself and find ways to become productive, but since I am a human with many mistakes and flaws, there are obviously some days where I am not as motivated as some days which I came to the conclusion that it is okay to take breaks.
negative_text: As a person living in this world, there are so many flaws that I have. One being that sometimes that I can not say no. It may not sound like a bad trait to have but it has come to many examples where I am being taken advantage of from many companions. I am also the type to be very sensitive. I do not take criticism very easily which I want to be able to, but my emotions get in the way. I blame myself and start thinking that I could have done better depending on the scenario. I sometimes cross boundaries where I feel like I am close to someone and start telling them about things that are unnecessary which has come to make me feel like it can be in a negative aspect in my life. I also tend to think I am worse at things than I am which makes me feel not confident in a lot of things such as when speaking in class. I sometimes would know the answer but I would be too scared to say it due to me not being confident and being scared of judgement. Although these may not seem to be super terrible traits, I have been in many scenarios where some parts of my personality can become negative in some aspects or even positive in some parts as well.

text: I think I have a very outgoing personality. Im always down for anything as long as I'm having a good time. Nothing is ever off limits. Im also caring and always make sure everyone around me is okay. I do get anxious a lot and stress for no reason and I always have to tell myself to stop. I'm always planning ten steps ahead and need to micro manage everything. Im funny and nice
negative_text: Id say a negative thing about me is that I sometimes can have a negative outlook on life when things don't go my way. I tend to complain about stupid things that don't matter and focus on the small stuff that I shouldn't. I tend to be able to let go when I need to and I hold onto things that hurt me.

text: I am quite independent and value my time alone, but enjoy being friendly with my roommates and developing a friendship.  I am communicative and open to different lifestyles as long as I am respected as well.  I like to laugh and live in a lively home.  My sleep schedule can be unpredictable, with me sometimes passing out on the couch at unusual hours of the night.  I am aware of the space that I take up and try to do what I can to make sure everyone feels comfortable.  I can be messy in my own way, but never to an extent of disgust especially in common areas.  I can be blunt and direct if needed, but I usually tend to avoid conflict and strive to have a peaceful living space.  I can be emotional and very self-reflective, but I keep this all to myself unless if I become friends with my roommate.  Then I would hope we could both feel comfortable enough to express our selves with each other.  I can both be really quiet and isolated sometimes, while at other times being outgoing, spontaneous, and philosophical in my life approach.
negative_text: When feeling stressed, burnt out, or tired I can definitely be easily irritable and cranky.  Also if my external environment is messy it can make me feel overwhelmed.  I am easily overstimulated and retreat when this occurs.  I can be pessimistic at times and enter depressive episodes which cause me to isolate and complain about my situation.  Often I experience emotions, but don't know how to process or feel them.  I overanalyze most things in life.  I can be stubborn at times too.  I can get absorbed in my own world, which causes me to forget that other people have complexities occurring in their lives as well.

text: My personality traits are agreeable and conscientious. I am quite an anxious person and I do tend to be the cleanest of the people I live with.  I have a lot of big feelings and I feel them very intensely sometimes so I do talk quite a bit about them. I am not very good at reading social cues so I can be very forward with the things I say and am somewhat lacking a filter. I enjoy bike riding, rock climbing, reading romance novels, and most kinds of painting. I tend to be a very busy person so I am not home much and I am often also stressed about my schedule. I am not conflict-avoidant and really work to have defined boundaries in all of my relationships. I have done a lot of work in crisis intervention both for mental health and emergency medical services so I am fairly level-headed when it comes to dealing with difficult situations. I love cats, and I also like dogs, but I feel guilty that I can't always be as excited as they are when they see me. I don't have any pets because my schedule is so demanding.
negative_text: I have seen a lot of violence through the jobs I work and struggle to feel safe at all times. The concept of a new person as a roommate is scary to me because I fear violence from people that I do not know. I have a close-knit support system that means the world to me and am afraid to extend beyond it. I haven't full processed a lot of what I have been through so most of the time I am not sure who I really am because I just feel like a shell of my former self. I try to be the type of person people feel safe around because that's what I really hope for in the people I meet. Other than that I am a really healthy, caring, kind, and thoughtful person.

text: I am pretty shy, but once I get comfortable, i open up. I like sharing a lot about myself, good and bad. I like to communicate about everything because I am an overthinker. I am also pretty selfless, i love helping others and seeing others happy, makes me happy
negative_text: I tend to be very petty. I can easily get mad over the smallest things. I have a lot of pet peeves and a lot of things annoy me.
