text:
Hey roomie!! Can't wait to room with you this year!! I would like to describe myself as a somewhat proactive and organized  person (although I do tend to procrastinate sometimes and go on spontaneous shopping sprees or coffee adventures. I am a huge relationship-oriented person, and I think that going through college really taught me that people will always be more important than your GPA. I grew up to be achievement-oriented, whether that be receiving top grades or doing phenomenal things in my extracurriculars as a leader. While college has definitely made me aware to the amount of super excelling people (definitely has humbled me), I still try to do my best to achieve and excel, while maintaining balance with my mental health and well-being. I am empathetic, open, and strive to be impartial; something that I despise the most is when people hear one side of the story and see that as truth. I realize that we all our entitled to our own opinions, biases, and other values, as we all grew up with different backgrounds. However, I believe that always being open to shift our lenses and perspectives to whatever issue that rises is super important in understanding each other and being kind, respectful people. I love my family, and I have pride of being an older sister. :) 

I have a TON of hobbies --- music being my primary one. I grew up with music for the past 15 years of my life as a classical pianist, flute section leader, and the first female junior drum major of my high school. I have a soft spot for anyone who loves music, or wants to learn music. Like my relationship with music, I believe that it's important that every person has an emotional outlet. While I consider myself extroverted, I also value my introspective/introverted times when I am by myself, as I feel like it's relaxing and it helps me calm down in a situation with a lot of noise, stress, and intensity. It is at these times I play piano.
I love watching anime, Korean dramas, and TV shows --- it's the second hobby that I spend most of my time on. Watching shows on my own is fun, but watching shows with my best friends while munching on my favorite snacks (Sweetheart french fries YES) is the best. 
I love hanging out with my friends, and a lot of these hangouts consist of some kind of food exploration (usually an aesthetic place or Korean soon tofu), and adventuring new places. My boyfriend is my main support system, and we do everything together. 
WOw this was so disorganized my thoughts are all over the place LOL
negative_text:
I tried to stay honest to myself in the description before, especially regarding my relationship with my academic achievements, career life. I think that accepting criticism and the traits that are not as positive has been an ongoing journey with myself, and that's completely healthy. I used to think that I am open and extroverted with basically anyone, but I actually find myself being exclusive with the people that I hang out with or talk to sometimes. Even though I tell myself and believe that everyone deserves a chance to be friends, I also go against that by being hesitant or even resistant in talking/hanging with particular people I don't know. (My boyfriend, on the other hand, thinks with the mentality of "the more people the merrier," which made my thoughts clearer.) I sometimes have a hard time sticking up for myself or what I want because of my people-pleaser mentality. I believe I improved, but I think that I can do better. 
I can be a little selfish --- for example, when I know that my boyfriend is tired, I still let him do the dishes for me anyway. It's a small, silly story, but that's the first example that popped up in my head.

text:
I would like to describe myself in 3 different personalities (as said by my friends):

1) Driven. I am the type of person that will always stay true to my passions and my dreams. Whether that be in medicine, public health, helping people out, singing, music, exercising, food, or with family and friends, I will always stay focused on my goals so I can be the best version of myself possible.

2) Caring. Not only am I a huge people person, but I would not hesitate to take a bullet for some of my closest friends and my family. I love the people around me and would sometimes put them over myself when times get tough for them, or even if they just need someone to talk to. It warms my heart to be able to make someone's day, and it keeps me going, even if I am feeling down myself. 

3) Weird. Whether it be my sense of humor, the way I dress (sometimes), or the lingo that I use, I am NOT someone that follows any sort of rules to fit in. I take pride in being WAY too comfortable at certain times--it's pretty clear that one should not burp in a room of silence, and imma do it again BAP BAP. Warning: don't worry, I am aware that there are extenuating circumstances when I should NOT do this, including professional environments, family dinners, and Psych 150. Everything else is fair game tho.
negative_text:
Here are some things that are "negative" about me:

1. I care too much. Although it is great to be caring about many people, it hurts sometimes because I may think someone is a close friend, but nothing's reciprocated. When someone is hurt, I get hurt too, and the more people I tend to care for, the more susceptible I am to being sad because of the downs that my friends and family go through.

2. Too comfortable. Remember when I said I am too comfortable with some of the stuff I do? Sometimes, it backlashes. I have had multiple people say that they were uncomfortable with the person I am due to my sense of humor or some of the rash remarks I make at times. I never mean anything ill-intentioned, however, sometimes it may be perceived as such, and its costed me greatly before.

3. I do not like being by myself. It is something that I am still learning to be comfortable with. Otherwise, I would always try to surround myself with people. Obviously, one should love themselves the most, but when it comes to me, I would much MUCH rather be with my friends and family rather than be alone.

text: I am a very friendly person who likes to talk to new people. Before I did not have many friends, never went to parties in high school and always felt out of place. However, ever since I came to Berkeley I started being more social and outgoing. I can also be a little straight forward when we start getting closer. I try to avoid conflict as much as possible with people because I don't like the feeling of causing drama. I can also be a very emotional person at times. I get also very anxious when I feel things are not going my way. Besides all of these emotions I am also very fun, I like to party, go out with my friends, and on a Friday night have a nice cocktail. I am always up for a new adventure if I have the time. I don't like making people feel out of place because I know the feeling and its not cool. I also like my alone time, there is a time during the day where I just want to be alone and not socialize with anyone, especially when it comes to doing homework or little things like walking to class. I enjoy listening to music when i walk to class and if someone is talking to be it takes away from my moments of peace.
negative_text: One negative trait that I left out was probably my temperament. I tend to get mad really fast and when I do I have no filter. Sometimes I say things that can hurt someone unintentionally. This probably comes from also being too emotional. I am also a little picky on how I like things done. For example, if I clean my side of the room I expect that person to clean it the same as I did. I get freaked out when theres a lot of clutter, especially on the walls. I like to be as minimalist as possible and having to many things really freaks me out. I also don't like it when people use my things or touch them or even move them. I get extremely anger at that and it causes a little bit of anxiety. I am constantly checking that my things are in the same place as I left them when I come back to my apartment.

text: I am both shy and outgoing at times, depending on how well I know you. But once I feel like I know you, you won't get me to shut up. I am passionate and have an opinion about everything, but am open-minded and love hearing others opinions and always am changing my own. For those who I care for, I will do anything to make them happy. I am blindly loyal, almost to a fault at times because once you earn my trust, I never waver. I love openly and voice how much I care often. I do get stressed easily, which goes away after I have solved what I deem the issue at hand. I am indecisive and find it hard picking a decision without thinking how my life would be different if I chose the other option. Once I know you, I will do everything in my favor to make you smile or laugh, but will use this to hide a lot of my feelings. I have a strong sense of adventure and often find myself feeling trapped if I don't follow the voice in the back of my head telling me to see the world. I am empathetic and often can find it difficult to separate my feelings from others. I seek grand adventure around the world, but what makes me happiest is a cup of coffee in the morning.
negative_text: While I tend to be a fairly positive person, I do find that I can slip into a negative mood fast if I am anxious, hungry, or tired. I can find it challenging to break out of these negative moods letting my brain overthink and spiral. I can be stubborn only if I am comfortable around you and have issues when I feel like people are not listening to me or when I feel misunderstood. I overthink far too often. I have trouble with voices of authority when I don't agree with the fundamental values they are preaching.

text: I am someone that is kind, empathetic, understanding, and caring. I am funny, patient, and open to learning about different points of view. I am very willing to have an open, honest conversation about our boundaries when it comes to sharing the same space. I am loyal and care a lot for my friends and family. I enjoy rock climbing, playing my ukulele and piano, singing, cooking, creating art, and listening to music to relax. I also like doing guided meditations and discussing topics related to mental health. I would describe myself as a nerd who enjoys Harry Potter, Percy Jackson, and the Hunger Games series. I am also an EMT and love being a part of the healthcare system to support our community. I am passionate about my cultural identity as a Thai American immigrant and hope to continue to foster a safe environment for Thai American students on campus.
negative_text: I would say I am quite an anxious person. I tend to get stressed and overwhelmed at times. I have a difficult time wanting to take on more responsibilities than I can handle. That being said, that is why I go to therapy and am continually working on trying to find balance. I understand my flaws, but am trying to do better to work on myself. I also know I have a tendency to take on other people's emotional labor, but have been working on taking on less (empathy's double edge-sword). I enjoy learning about mindfulness and grounding techniques, which I use to help me when I am stressed. I tend to be prepared for the worst case scenario. I also believe in the best in people. I am an activist.

text: I would say that I am an ambivert, as I have both extraverted and introverted tendencies. I feel that I make more of an effort to ask questions and keep the conversation going when I am with someone who is more introverted than I am, but I do less talking and make less of an effort to keep the conversation going when I am with someone who is more extraverted than me. I am definitely more introverted though, as I definitely run out of social battery at social events and big gatherings, and I feel more comfortable and at peace in my room. I would definitely prefer staying home doing my own thing than going out with people. I also do not really like small talk, as I find it awkward and uncomfortable, such as when forced to talk with classmates next to me in class. I do not go out of my way to make new friends in any of my classes either. I would say I am also very emotional and sensitive. I would say that I am very sympathetic, and I always try to put myself in other people’s shoes before behaving a certain way/taking action or saying something. I find myself constantly putting others before me, which sometimes is damaging and hurtful to myself, but I am happier when I am able to help others. I also find happiness in other people’s happiness. I would also say that I am pretty good at reading others and quickly catching onto things/reading the room. I can immediately tell if someone’s mood changes, or if they are feeling down or something has happened to them. I consider myself a strong people pleaser. Oftentimes, I find myself caring more about what other people think than about my own thoughts. On that note, I think I do struggle with being self-conscious a lot and being wary of other people’s views and thoughts of me. As I mentioned earlier, I am very emotional and sensitive. I take a lot of things to heart, and I tend to overthink a lot. I overanalyze and overthink about many things, and very often, too. I cry very easily; I cry when watching films and reading books, and I also cry when I am sad or when I am angry. I would say my emotions definitely control me more than I control them. My mood also changes very quickly, so I am up and down a lot.
negative_text: I did mention this in the first part, but I am very sensitive and emotional. Therefore, I tend to take things to heart a lot, and get hurt easily over small things that most likely are not very significant and do not even matter much. I let my emotions control me a lot more than I control them, so I have a lot of mood swings. I also have a short temper, so while I try my best to not show that side of me to friends and peers, I do get irritated and angry easily/often at home, which I always end up regretting after the moments pass. I also am highly sensitive, so I get really annoyed easily and a lot. For instance, if someone acts in a way that is not to my liking, I get annoyed with them. I am very sensitive to noise as well, so loud noises easily scare me and I get very irritated and annoyed around loud people. I also strongly dislike people who are rude and do not have basic manners, especially in public. I am also pretty impatient, along with my short temper.

text: I am someone who is introverted when you first meet them but then becomes loud, responsive, and extroverted if I feel comfortable around you. I am often mentioned as someone who is bubbly, enthusiastic, willing to do anything, etc. I often feel happy and excited but sometimes I feel tired and my social clock has run dry and just need time to myself. I love being the life of the party but I also like being by myself in my room curled up with a good book away from reality. I am an overly anxious person and even sometimes paranoid thinking who opened that door I thought I shut it at least 20 times a day when in fact I was probably the one that opened the door. I often like to watch Netflix or read a book and escape reality. But I also like being active on my feet doing various activities. I would say I generally am a kind person who has a big heart and I care very much for other human beings. I just want everyone to be happy in life. That said I am very opinionated on certain things. Mainly that human life comes first. I normally want to please everyone. I also am so indecisive it is crazy. Like I can't even decide what I want for dinner or what I want to read next. I hate making decisions and normally love when people do it for me. I like things the way I like things which is hard. I also hate small noises and get really anxious and annoyed at things like other people eating, people typing on their computers, chewing hum, etc. I  am a very particular person but I know that. I hate making new friends, I like for things to stay the same and it is hard for me to branch out and change my ways. text:
Hi there! My name is Hope Hawkins and I consider myself to be a pretty kind and generous person. I love surprising people with gifts. If I see something while I'm out one day and it reminds me of you, I'll likely pick it up and gift it to you. I have a person policy that I try to live by, which is to try and venmo people as little as possibly. When you constantly venmo for meals, trips, etc. I think that takes away from your relationship with someone because it breaks dow trust and generosity between people. I like to say "I'll get it this time, and you can get it next time." I also consider myself a pretty artsy person. I used to be really into acting, and I do still enjoy it, but I don't perform as often now. I love painting as well and playing the ukulele. Arts and crafts in general are my thing!

 I have been told I'm pretty smart, but I didn't really start believing it until recently. I think I am much more of an english/writing/social sciences person rather than a hardcore STEM person, which may be where that insecurity has come from in the past. Someon who is stereotypically very smart seems to always be into math or physics or something. I also really love to journal. It gives me some quiet peaceful time, and I enjoy the self-reflection. I tried to keep a gratitude journal for a while, but I;'m someone who is bad at doing things super consistently. I always say I'm going to dosomething every day, but then I get off track. The only thing I am even close to being that consistent about is brushing my teeth and doing my skincare routine.

I really like giving back to people as well. I am working as behavior technician for autisic kids, and I am having so much fun doing it! I have learned through this job that I really enjoy working with kids, it's always a fun environment. I also find a lot of fulfillment doing this job because I greatly feel like it matters a lot. That's why I wouldn't want to go into more businessy jobs like consulting. I feel like I'm a very intrinsicly motivated person and when I thoroughly enjoy and care about something I will REALLY give it my all. But at the same time, if I am not intrinsicly motivated about something, it is EXTREMELY hard to motivate myself to do it and put good effort in.
negative_text: I definitely do have many flaws. I think I mentioned motivation last time, which is also a negative side of me. I tend to procrastinate a lot, and I am not easily motivated to do things I don't really have an interest in. I also definitly don't exercise as much as I should. I could definitely be healthier in that aspect. I think I can have a little bit of an ego at times, particularly when it comes to physical appearance. I think I am a pretty attractive person and it can definitely cross over into the vain area. This one is a lot harder to write about. I also think I am not good at confrontation. If someone does something or says something that bothers me, I'll most likely never bring it up. I'm still learning how and when to stand up for myself. I think sometimes I don't surround myself with the best people either, so I guess I have a lot to learn from this personality class.

text:
Future roomie, 
Don’t be surprised if I come home freaking out about how it only took me 20 minutes to reach our room. You’ll understand my enthusiasm when I tell you about the countless hours I’ve spent in Nigeria’s traffic (in pidgin: go-slow) for my whole life. You’ll hear more pidgin when I’m filming TeaTime episodes (feel free to join!). I may code-switch between Indian and American when calling my family every day. Yes, every day, meaning my family is now and forevermore your family. 

Roomie, what's the meaning of life? Do you believe in soulmates? What's your attachment style? Essentially, I love late-night chats about everything from social phenomena to existential questions. They're weirdly perfect mental breaks, leading to new perspectives and guaranteed hilarity. These range from minutes to hours - so join me as we attempt to uncover life's truths while disastrously cooking (unless you can cook - that would be great). 

You may not get away with feeling down without me noticing. When you randomly receive adorable animal GIFs or iced coffees on your desk, know it’s with love...and to check in on you. If you don’t want to talk about it, we can listen to my ‘get up, get moving’ playlist - because music can help turn a frown upside down. ;) Seriously though, whenever you need pick-me-ups, either physically to boost energy levels with my turmeric health shots, or mentally by having someone to listen, I’m here. 

I hope you love spontaenous trips and listening to music to accompany daily activities - because I sure do! I love taking time to explore new genres of music or new areas of the city. I think I would explain myself as an extreme social butterfly that also enjoys chill night's in (occasionally). I also love painting and expressing myself creatively - so I would love to have paint nights and room redecorations. I think I can get bored easily, but once something interests me I can go into hours and hours of deep diving to learn more. I would say I feel emotions a lot and I feel them very strongly. I express myself through... random screaming and singing. But don't worry - you'll be able to tell that I'm just letting out frustration or excitement. I am admittedly a night owl and ashamedly not the tidiest person. But I will have random outbursts of energy to clean up our room and my spaces. The messiness of my side of the room can be directly correlated with how stressed/anxious I am - tip to understand me better. I am a hopeless romantic but in the most hopeful way haha - i love romanticizing life and the small serendipities of every day. 

To years of cheers, tears, and conversations in our ears!

text:
Personality is the unique mix of characteristics that defines how we think, feel, and act across different situations and over time. It’s like our personal style of interacting with the world, influencing everything from our choices in friends and careers to how we handle stress or celebrate successes. 
I'm friendly and easygoing, always curious, and love deep discussions. I'm respectful of personal space but enjoy sharing meals or a movie night. My hobbies include reading, exploring music events, and windsurfing. I value clear communication and a tidy space, and I'm always open to new experiences and ideas.  I prefer creating a friendly environment over toxic behaviors. 
Psychologists dig into these traits to understand what drives us to behave in certain ways. They look at how we deal with ups and downs, celebrate good times, and manage relationships. Getting to know these aspects of personality can help us understand ourselves and others better, leading to improved self-awareness and healthier relationships. It's like having a map that helps navigate the complex journey of life, highlighting our strengths and areas where we can grow.  
Imagine it as a specific set of ingrained habits of thought and emotion, interwoven with our actions, that makes each of us distinctly who we are. These traits are quite stable; they don’t change easily, though they can evolve with life’s experiences and as we grow. 
Our personality is shaped by a dyad of our genetic makeup and our life experiences. The family, culture, and social circles we grow up in all throw in bits and pieces that stick with us, influencing how we see the world and behave within it. For instance, one person might be naturally outgoing, thriving on social interaction, while another might prefer the quiet, introspective solitude.

text: I am someone who is very friendly and can be very outgoing. I believe that there is always hope, and even though I can get stuck in negative moods I always circle back to positivity. text:

I am a Registered Yoga Instructor, so I am very into health and fitness. I also love being outside and going on walks and hikes. However, I do enjoy resting and not doing much on occasion. 

I would say that I am pretty clean and organized. I like having a clean space around me, although I am not a neat freak who needs things to be perfect all of the time. negative_text:
I touched on this earlier, but a negative characteristic about my personality is that I have a slight temper and I am very direct/to the point with people I feel comfortable with. I think that in the back of my mind, I feel as if these individuals will not go anywhere, so I do not mind being direct/harsher with them. For example, when my sister does something which really bothers me and we get in a fight, I can say some mean things to her which I later regret. I get very heated in the moment and then I regret acting out when I am more calm. Another example is when my boyfriend used something of mine without asking, and in the moment, I was so angry and called him names. This is definitely wrong and I think that I am so comfortable with him that in the moment, I did not think anything of it. However, when I calmed down, I regretted making it such a big deal. 

Another aspect of my personality is that it is hard for me to trust people, and I think this influences my relationships. I am also slightly a perfectionist/obsessive about things, and hold myself to very high standards. text: I try very hard to be a good person. It's not that I want to impress others, but that I want to be proud of myself and not have regrets or guilt. I suffered horrific child abuse and I don't want to be like my abuser in any way. I suffer from depression and anxiety, and that does influence my personality. I don't get very happy or excited, and it's very difficult for me to not have my guard up around other people and sometimes around myself. I was raised by very prejudiced people, and I try to always remain conscious of that. I have some prejudices that I recognize and haven't been able to completely eliminate. I try to be open-minded but I'm sometimes reminded that I'm not as open-minded or accepting as I want to be. My drive to be better causes me to lose patience with people who are acting thoughtlessly or carelessly, but in most other situations I can be very patient. I tend to be introverted more than extroverted, and conscientious rather than carefree. I try to strive towards ideals, but I have a very realist view of the world. I have a pretty low opinion of the average person, and I see a lot of people making mistakes or foolish or selfish decisions that to me seem almost effortless to avoid. I don't like my world very much, so I want to change it for the better, but I get stressed and depressed worrying that it won't be possible. I do think there are great people out there, but there aren't many of them and their environment deprives them of the chance to realize their potential. My worldview sounds very cynical, but I think it's just realistic. I'm not very talkative normally, but when someone else opens up a conversation it's easier for me to talk a lot.

I don't drink often or do any substances, which isn't bad but I feel it deprives me of a lot of chances for social interactions. I don't really have any friends. (Just realized the prompt asks me to describe myself to a new roommate, so here I got.) 
Hello, my name is Raghav. I like keeping personal space private and would therefore not prefer having friends over. It's not because I'm not social but I like to protect my personal space. When I want to be social, I'd prefer to do it outside in a space meant for socializing. 

I like keeping spaces healthy and uncluttered, both literally and energetically. 

I like being health physically and mentally too. Good nutrition, sleep and exercise mean a lot to me. 

For mental health, I like to meditate and regularly spend time with friends. I often see spending time with people more of an obligatory activity in order to stay mentally and socially healthy instead of something I choose to do for fun. 

I find myself socially unaware at times so I believe that forced social contact is healthy and will allow me to move out of my comfort zone. 

I realize that rooming with me might sound a lot and I usually wouldn't say these things but I am because I have been asked to describe my personality and this is probably honestly what I think of myself.

text:
There are some parts of my personality that have always been the same:
I care about school
I am deeply curious and I want to know everything everything everything
I get frustrated easily if I don't immediately catch on to a skill 
I love dogs, fireworks, and the ocean.
I am talkative and I have to work hard at active listening.
I am a logical person.
I am pretty arrogant, or confident in my abilities, or whatever you want to call it (but arrogant seems pretty spot-on to me).
I have an aggressive moral compass, especially when it comes to lying.  
I think that I am a good person.

I was taking the Phase 1 RPP requirement survey and I realized that my responses have changed a good bit since last semester.  There are things that I have always thought to be true about myself that perhaps no longer are.
I have always been so sure of myself, and so confident in recent years that things will be Okay.  Now, I am very worried about the state of our world, as well as my ability to accomplish all I have set out to be.  Not being arrogant is a new feeling for me.  I'm not sure I like it.
I am quieter than I used to be.  I am better at active listening.  I get drained more easily when I spend time with groups of people.
I feel myself being dictated to by my emotions.  I try to rationalize them, to do what reason says is the smart thing to do, and it's harder than it has been in the past.  I am panicky, I am overwhelmed, and making lists that show how much I have to do just aren't cutting it.

Some other things about me:
I have less patience than I should have for people who I view as less competent than I am.
I am a freak for religion and for history
I am also a freak for keeping things clean.
I donate to charity regularly - time and money -, but maybe I do it more to assuage my own guilt about my privilege than to actually do good.  I don't think that's true, but the thought that I am secretly not a Generous or Good person keeps me up at night.

This isn't the assignment, but I hope it's okay.
negative_text:
I think that by ignoring the assignment - by writing what I really thought instead of writing what I would say to a roommate - I gave a  more accurate description that I generally would.  

In actually describing myself to a roommate, I would emphasize:
I need a lot of sleep
I am really really clean.
I like to have time together and time alone - the former is important for my happiness, the second for my sanity
I enjoy shitty reality TV that I feel bad for watching.
I tell people that I'm not funny but I secretly think that I am.
I can be conflict avoidant, but less so than some other people.   I am still scared of conflict, but I try to tackle that by being straightforward when I am bothered.   I think that most people are okay with this, but it bothers some people.
I care about doing the right thing a lot, so much that it is sometimes hard to look out for my mental health in this world where all the heartache is just a click away
I hope that no one is reading this, and I feel very vulnerable just writing it.

text: In general, I'm not the most easygoing individual. I'm competitive, not only when it comes to things that are important but also with regard to trivial matters and games. I tend to form judgements about people very quickly, and while these judgements are somewhat malleable I tend to be a victim of confirmation bias when it comes to labeling people as "friend" or "not friend." That is to say, once I've formed a first impression about a person, my idea of who they are is unlikely to change quickly. I promise that I'm fun most of the time, though; I get a lot of laughs out of people and love to play practical jokes. I certainly can be polarizing, as I have a strong personality. I'm rambunctious and goofy, but also can get fierce when I feel like I'm competing with someone -- whether that's in a classroom, on a basketball court, or elsewhere. Some people find my tenacity to be motivating, but I can see where it would be off-putting. Oh, I also think of myself as pensive. I try to think critically about existential issues and sometimes people find things that I say to be profound. Perhaps it's evident from that last statement that I'm not the most humble individual, but that's something that I'm working on. In short, I'm a bit of a paradox. I think of myself as an intellectual, but also someone who's not above pettiness, as someone who's constantly improving but has a long way to go.
negative_text: I left out one of my best qualities, which is my loyalty. I'm a fiercely loyal individual, and I do things for my friends that most other people wouldn't. It's perhaps a bit trite to say this, but I'm the type of person who will put others above myself -- when I deem them worthy of my loyalty. I've hosted parties at my own house, volunteered to be a designated driver, and taken inebriated friends from my house to their own, only to turn around and drive back to my place late in the night. That's not an incredible sacrifice, I'm sure that there are examples of greater magnitude that I could think up given more time, but I can't think of another person in my friend group who's done that. I also left out the fact that I strive to be a role model for my younger sisters, leading by example in school, with how I treat people, and in other domains. I see that this was asking for "perhaps more negative" facets of me, but I feel like I figuratively threw myself under the bus in the last section so I wanted to balance things out. I think I left out my better traits in the previous exercise.

text: I would describe my personality traits as adventurous, calm, and kind. I would then explain why I believe I fit each of the traits. I believe I am adventurous because I am always looking for something new to do and am always open to many new opportunities no matter how out of the way they are for me. I also am always going on random midday adventures and sort of allow myself to not have a repeating schedule that way every day can feel new. I believe I am calm as I actively use breathing techniques when I get into stressful situations as to prevent myself from getting overwhelmed. I also do these exercises to keep myself from getting irrationally angry as I enjoy communicating out issues and trying to resolve things in a productive manner. Lastly I believe I am kind as most of the things I do are for other people. I always go out of my way to help people and want to provide therapy for free in the future for people in my town as a way of giving back to my community. I would describe my feelings as a generally happy individual who always tries to see the good in every day. I always treat each day as a new day in order to avoid carrying lots of anguish and sadness inside. When I do get overwhelmed with sadness or anger I try to calm down by either crying or letting my frustrations out and talking to those who I love the most. My favorite activities consist of playing videogames, hanging out with my friends, and living life to the fullest by doing random things everyday.
negative_text: Some of the negative aspects about myself that I left out are that I can be bossy sometimes. I am a clean freak so when things get messy or stay messy for longer than a week then I begin to ask people to pick up the slack and clean with them. I am also very forgetful about important things which leads to me forgetting about promises I make with people. I always intend to keep them but I struggle to remember everything that happens in my day-to-day life. I sometimes feel like I deserve to be treated better by people because I do kind things and I had a hard life and if I think about it too much it puts me in a funk and makes me feel worse about myself. I constantly struggle to maintain a balance between feeling good because I help people and feeling bad because I wish more people recognized my good and respected me for it. I also do not take criticism very well. I used to be worse at it but I try to take people's word with good intentions but it always makes me feel subpar to them. It makes me feel like I am not as good as everyone else and I never will be.

text: I would describe myself as a very dedicated and friendly person. I give my full attention to everything I do which includes how I treat the people around me. negative_text: I can be passive aggressive when I have an issue with someone or something. I don’t like being very confrontational, but this results in me bottling my emotions instead of directly addressing the issue. I can get jealous of others sometimes, but I don’t really act on that. I think my anger is my biggest negative trait, because I visualize things occurring in a “proper” or “correct” way when in reality there is no one perfect way to handle a situation or express yourself. This difference in my idealized reality and the reality that occurs upsets me and I get frustrated because I would like to think other people would also agree with my assumptions about how a situation should be played out, but it’s impossible for that to always be the case. I also feel betrayal too hard, and I let my sadness control me when it involves people I care about. If I can’t figure out why my friend is upset at me or why I can’t help someone close to me, I see myself as problematic and view myself in an unhealthy way.

text: Hi! I would describe myself as relatively introverted, and I really value having a bit of alone time every day. However, I love getting to know people, and I would say that I generally enjoy talking to strangers. Many acquaintances and even close friends describe me as seemingly extroverted because I'm willing to put myself out there. Although I always get a little nervous in many social situations, I like to do this because I think talking to people and getting to know others/hearing their stories is what makes life meaningful. I find that human connections is one of the driving forces being my decisions and goals in life. I'm also a very emotional person, but it takes me a long time to begin trusting someone before divulging and confiding in them. It's nothing personal against any individual, but I have always been a fairly independent person. I have difficulties asking for help, and it's something that I think I'm becoming better at gradually. I don't like to make generic small talk, but I am generally seeking deeper conversations (that being said, I am often silly and goofy with my friends). I can be a cynical and pessimistic person, but more in the sense that I'm realistic about what the worst scenario is. I'm much harder on myself than I am on other people. I love deeply, and when I decide to trust someone, it's because I see them as (hopefully) being in my life for the long term. It takes me a long time to develop feelings (romantically), but once I do, I don't see myself getting over said feelings anytime soon. I feel emotions very strongly, but it's not always obvious to others. I generally see the best in people until proven otherwise, but I think some of my interactions in life have made me less optimistic about people's intentions. I would describe myself as a warm person in that I am generally friendly and welcoming towards anyone I interact with; however, if that energy is not reciprocated over time, I will be more neutral in my interactions with someone. I care deeply about those close to me, and if someone hurt the people important to me, I would be more than willing to take action and speak up for them. However, I am more hesitant to do the same for myself. I think in some ways, although I wouldn't say I lack self-confidence, I do view others as almost more "deserving" than me. I also like to keep myself busy; I say it's because I want to make the most out of life, but I think part of it comes from a fear that I'm never doing enough. Anything I do in life is because I want to do it; if I don't enjoy it, I will not stay just because it'll benefit my future professional goals. I hope to leave an impact on at least one person in my life.
negative_text: I get irritated easily, especially when I'm stressed or overworked. There have been situations when I have not been the most emotionally mature, and I don't have a lot of patience for re-explaining myself. In the past, I have blown up at others, and I let the anger get the best of me despite knowing that the other person didn't have bad intentions. In recent years, I think I've become much better at managing my emotions. I would also say that I have a tendency to isolate myself when I'm not feeling well, and I will push others away even if they want to help. I am not always the most considerate of other people's feelings, and I would say that I'm selfish, in the sense that I will almost always put my own wants and needs first. I think I'm fairly empathetic, and I sometimes have difficulty separating myself from my work; for example, if I'm helping someone and something doesn't go well, I can sometimes take it personally. I also get lost in my mind easily and often.

text: Hello future roommate, I'm excited to meet you! I am a generally introverted person in that I enjoy having my own time to recharge and enjoy spending time alone, but my close relationships are also one of the most important things to me. I love to spend time with friends and close family members, and building these relationships is a major goal of mine. I would say that I am conscientious, detail-oriented, and can be a perfectionist, known as the "type A" person, though I think the extent of this depends on who I am around. I can also find myself being more laid back and carefree when around people I am very comfortable with. I like to be efficient, get things done, and then have time to relax and recharge as I see fit during the day.
negative_text: One negative thing about my personality is that I feel like I can have a high level of anxiety or perhaps neuroticism when I get in an irritated mood, and can be very specific and detail-oriented about things, so when things don't go as well, these levels can increase. I think that I also have the tendency to be hot and cold with certain people, which is a reaction to protecting myself and my own feelings, especially when I still need to process how I feel inside before expressing that view to the other person. I think this stems from what I believe to be my fearful avoidant attachment style that results from my experience during childhood with my parents in having to protect my emotions while others are acting inconsistently around me, which causes me to act inconsistently myself. I also think an important part of my personality is that, while personality is a stable thing, different facets of my personality wane and wax across time as I grow up and learn more about myself.

text: I believe that I am a nice person and often kind sometimes. I believe that because I intentionally try to go out of my way to welcome others, keep communal spaces clean, and always make sure to check in with others and how they are feeling. I consider myself a loyal friend, daughter, and sister. I always aim to be there for my friends and family, as they are important to me, and I love making them laugh. I'm a huge fan of comedy and anything that's remotely funny; I think I like to bring joy to others, and I do my best job in trying to make myself and others laugh. In terms of my lifestyle, I like to enjoy myself and indulge in the occasional college party, but more as a way to be an unhinged college student. I also tend to stress out over the smallest things, and I try to make things as perfect as possible the first time around, or I probably won't try doing it again. I am quite a forgetful person, so I try to make calendar events for things or write things down as a way to remember. I enjoy keeping to myself, and I like my alone time; however, too much alone time will end up in me ruminating in my own thoughts. I prefer to keep things neat and clean, as I am a slight germaphobe, but after studying abroad, I've learned to tackle my fear of germs in new ways (or even lessen my fear of it). I would like to emphasize "slight" because there are many things that most germaphobes do that I don't, I just have a greater affinity for keeping things neat, clean, and sanitary. I don't really have a great sense of fashion, but that's something I'm working on. I think clothing is a huge extension of personality, and I try to keep my palette quite neutral with earthy tones. If I were to be a color, I would be a dark forest green. Not only because dark forest greens are my favorite colors, but I think they represent my personality quite well. Paired with golden tones, I can be very warm, bright, and inviting. Paired with other neutral tones (like brown, beige, and other greens), I can be very cool, calm, and collected (despite struggling with social anxiety).
negative_text: I can definitely be someone who is anal about the small things. As I previously mentioned, I pay close attention to details, I like keeping things neat, clean, and sanitary. Not everyone has grown with the same standards or in the same household, so I understand that my living habits are different, and I certainly hope that it's not the most negative thing about me. However, I am quite a non-confrontational, passive-aggressive person. If things don't go my way or if I'm upset, there's a good chance that the other person will not know, but all my friends will. I try not to talk poorly behind people's backs, but I know I do that on the occasion when I'm having a "hard time" navigating through issues in relationships like friends and family. Another negative thing about my personality is that I tend to care about looks a bit more—but I hold others to the same standard as I hold for myself.
