negative_text: I am not very patient at all. I tend to give people respect and trust who do not deserve it. i would say in general I trust people way too easily. I can be very blunt and sometimes not aware of how my words, opinions, and thoughts affect other people until it is too late. I am also very stubborn, I like to things my way and it tends to take me awhile to see past my own ways.

text: I would describe myself as someone who is shy at first but once I get comfortable and trust someone I'm very outgoing. I enjoy going on hikes and exploring nature with friends. There are days when I like to feel calm and prefer to stay at home and just relax without feeling stressed. I have empathy with people and because of that people come to me and trust me,
negative_text: Some of the negative personality traits that I have is that I don't really express my emotions so there are many times when I don't tell anyone about my feelings. Another negative trait is that I don't communicate well or express my feelings well to other people. I also tend to be really stubborn and this can cause problems with other people, but on the other hand I reflect about these events.

text: I'd describe myself as someone who likes to be tidy and organized. I do not like when others in the household touch my belongs because there is a chance of it being misplaced and lost. I am also a night owl who prefers doing a few things in the night whether that is doing homework or reading, etc. I would say I am also a forgiving person. If something were to happen (like misplacing an item of mine) i can usually move on unless it is important. I enjoy taking walks. I am not a morning person, i enjoying doing most things at night. I like taking showers at night as well. I try my best to tidy up every other night or so, just to avoid a messy space. I can defintely say if i have a chaotic and unorganized space, I feel the same mentally. I enjoy making meals at home. I am relatively a happy person but I tend to get stressed especially under pressure. I am very introverted so I have a difficult time becoming expressive or social in a unknown environment. when it comes to an individual alone with me, i try my best to make conversation but i find it a lot more easier to make conversation with someone who is extroverted or describe themselves outgoing or slightly talkative. when it comes to very extroverted individuals I tend to get a bit overstimulated or feel like the person may be too much for my personality.
negative_text: I would say I can typically get slightly irritated with soemone who may be unorganized. I am not the nicest when completing a task under preassure, especially if it involves another person helping me complete that task. I am anxious, and i can get anxious very easily to the point where I rather stay indoors or in my bedroom. I want to say i often react emotionally. Ironically, I can be half way done with a task but let future me deal with it later. I still try to clean up but I do have my moments where i get tired. I dont know if being a sleep person is a negative trait but I enjoy sleeping a lot. I am also a hungry person

text: I would describe my own personality as compassionate, hardworking, lovable, and intelligent. I am very outgoing and a social butterfly when placed in a public setting, and love meeting new people! I am not aggressive or mean to others. I try and consider others' feelings in certain situations before my own. I am diligent with work and whatever tasks are thrown at me. I am great at communicating with others and work well in team environments. I am an over-thinker and hate procrastinating. I am athletic and like to participate in physical activities like hiking, swimming, etc. I like aesthetics, and love when things just fit together (note-taking, photography). I am a night owl and do not like waking up too early.
negative_text: If I can add on more qualities, I would say that I am a pretty emotional person. I am in touch with my feelings, and will be very outspoken about them. Whether those feelings are sad or happy. I am stressed a lot of the time. As I said before, I am an over thinker, which causes me to get anxious and stressed out a lot. I am very spiritual and intuitive. I like to do affirmations and meditate when I have time. Sometimes I am materialistic and therefore I strive to work in a career path that can accommodate this.

text: my personality is complex. i overthink it all the time how i actually am internally vs how others perceive me. i always overthink how to express myself and i dont think people ever really get to know who i really am. i am someone who grew up in two different worlds--immigrant family and the western world so i feel like my identity was always confusing to me from a young age. i see myself code switching my personality and interests depending on the people i am around. that part doesn't matter as much as the person i am now and aspiring to be. i am an introverted person who finds comfort in being alone. when i meet someone new, it takes me a while to open up and be comfortable because i like to know who they are as a person and i feel safe around them being myself. i am someone who cares a lot but will not necessarily show it either. my personality is shown through actions whether that is being a listening ear and participating as an active friend in their life. i like to make people laugh and have meaningful conversations. also, just be in each others presence doing whatever respective task we have to do in our individual lives.
negative_text: i feel like at times i can become very involved in my own head, i make a narrative where i feel like no one really cares for me or will be there in the long run. overtime, i purposely find flaws in people and start to not like them and eventually not want to be around them as much. i think that is just me projecting on my own insecurities because i have never received validation of some sort before. i also tend to be closed off, not trusting of other people, and to myself which can be uninviting for many.

text: I am a considerate and thoughtful person. I try to think of others' needs and put them before mine. I try to be helpful when I can. I am usually patient, but unfair situations make me furious. I am respectful of other people's space, ideas, and beliefs. I like to usually stay in. I need some 'me-time' in a day. I have a moderate to low social battery. I can be shy. Very often, I feel unconfident which makes me even quieter. I am observant. I can sometimes overshare about myself, but I am good at keeping other people's secrets. I love working and studying. Sometimes, when I feel hurt, I spiral and feel those emotions very strongly, but I am trying to learn how to regulate them. I am persistent and determined. My thoughts can be chaotic, but I love organizing things.
negative_text: When I feel emotions very deeply, I spiral. It is quite common for me to catastrophize my standing in life in comparison to others and spiral very fast. This demotivates me and causes me to have a breakdown. There are phases when this happens very frequently. Since recognizing this, I have tried to work on it. I can also be paranoid sometimes and believe that no one cares about me, but rather everyone will hurt me or betray me someday. I am also trying to work on this and trying to trust people more.

text: I am organized and very clean. I've lived with other before and know the responsibilities that come with sharing a room such as cleaning up after myself, being considerate of time and noise, sharing the kitchen and room when needed, and giving space. I enjoy physical activity and waking up early. I am quiet and reserved. I enjoy my space and time and like to focus on my academic and work. I am hardworking and diligent therefore my time for those things are important to me and I like to have a quiet and clean space when I am working. I can be loud when I have to call my family. I don't often hear myself getting loud so Ill just start yelling and laughing. However if you tell me to quiet down I will listen and I am open to feedback and compromising on things if needed. I can definitely talk things out and appreciate talking about stuff such as when people are coming over or when we need a specific room for guests/ activities. I like things such as chores to be fair and I would appreciate everyone switching things around once and awhile. I am particular about my stuff so losing stuff or taking things without asking does bother me. I can share my things with others but as long as its returned in the same way. I can also get bothered when there is poor communication about an issue. Open communication is really important for me. However, if something bothers me sometimes I wont say anything to avoid conflict. I am scared of confrontation and sometimes I wont say anything even if its standing up for my needs or comfort. Generally I stay at home and only like to be out during the day. I go to sleep early and wake up early. I am focused on my priorities and generally dont like when plans get in the way of stuff Ive already planned out.
negative_text: I get upset when people get in the way of my plans or stuff doesnt work out the way I had imagined it would. I dont like when people are inconsiderate of my time and space and I can sometimes be passive aggresive about it. If you point out something that I think isnt true or not accurate Ill be passive aggressive. I can be too quiet and when people try to talk to me I'm short and maybe a little harsh so they stop talking to me. With people Im more comfortable with I try to be honest but sometimes it comes off really blunt and a little rude. I assume things about people and can be rude because of it and when I realize Im wrong and just distance myself and am too embarrassed to say anything. When I am really busy and stressed out I get annoyed by little things and take it out on people. I sometimes am not aware of how I sounds or come off until someone points it out and then I shut down. When people confront me about stuff that makes me uncomfortable I shut down and stop talking to others or just hide in my room or bury myself in work.

text: I am a really talkative person, and I’m pretty outgoing. I do like to be alone sometimes, but usually only for an hour or two a day. I like being active.I go to the gym, swim, walk, hike. I also love board games and baking. I like to think I am pretty empathetic, but one of my pet peeves is when people arrogantly say they are an “empath.” I’ve been told I’m too nice and that people take advantage of that. I wear my heart on my sleeve, but I’ve been working on being more tough skinned. I think I’m really funny, and I laugh a lot, pretty much all the time. I really like traveling, even though I can’t travel very often due to school an finances. I would like to think that I work really hard, sometimes I can be a bit lazy and procrastinate things, but overall I have a lot of ambition for my life and will work hard to achieve those goals. I really love children, I think they’re so cute and funny, bit also smarter than a lot of people give them credit for. I tend to overthink things a little bit and get into my own head, especially when I have a lot going on or I’m stressed. I really enjoy singing, I’ve been singing since I could talk. I sing pretty often to music or just little tunes while I’m walking around or getting ready. My music taste varies quite a bit, I listen to pop, rock, country, r&b, Disney, a little bit of rap, show tunes. I’m just not a fan of EDM, and most rap. I also really love Italy, I studied abroad there and desperately want to go back. I’m trying to learn Italian, but it is a lot harder when I’m not immersed in the language. I also love dogs. A lot of people have described me as having golden retriever energy, or Labrador energy. But I love playing with dogs and cuddling with them. I don’t have a dog myself, but I typically get very attached to my friends’ dogs. I do really want a dog, when I graduate I’m planning to adopt a dog since I’ve always wanted one. I also love the water, being in pools, by the beach, lakes, anything like that. I’ve noticed I will get a bit sad if I go a long time without being near the water.
negative_text: I overthink things a lot, especially in the last si months. I’ve been going through a difficult time, so I find that I’m a lot angrier and frustrated than I usually am. I typically see things on the bright side and consider myself to be optimistic, but that has been really difficult for me recently. I also have been told I talk too much, so I try to work on that, but sometimes I think that causes me to hide what I’m thinking and my true personality when I’m trying not to annoy anyone. I also hold grudges for a long time. I won’t do anything about them, but I do stay angry at people if they do something to really upset me. I’m very protective of the people that I love, probably too much. Once I form an opinion of someone, it is pretty difficult to change my mind. I also occasionally have panic attacks, usually when I’;m going through something particularly difficult, but a lot of the time I feel like I’m overreacting. I am also pretty gullible and I think people try to take advantage of that to manipulate me, but I’m so afraid of making people mad at me that I usually go along with it until its too late.

text: I have never experienced living with a person that I have never met in my life and imaging being with a roommate seems almost impossible. But if I ever do encounter situations like this, the first thing I will do is introduce myself to the roommate. Explaining your own personality to one person seems very difficult to someone you have just met in my opinion. I feel that it is important in building trust with the person first in order to present true personalities. With this in mind, first impressions are key and important at all times. I will do my absolute best to be approachable with the roommate by showing an overall comfortable personality and explain little things about myself such as my favorite hobbies and activities.
negative_text: I believe that I have the tendency to point out the negative aspects about myself more than the positives. For example, I have the tendency to have difficulty in planning out my schedule. Currently, I have about 10 different jobs. The two big jobs I work for is being a TSA coordinator at a resort called Terranea Resort and Covid Test provider for 10 different schools that contain about 200 students each.

text: I am initially a relatively shy person (especially when I am around people I am meeting for the first time) but i gradually come out of my shell as I become more comfortable around my friends and peers. Along this same idea, I think my closest friends would probably call me an extrovert – because I sometimes seem very outgoing or talkative with others – , but I really think I am more of an introvert with extroverted tendencies (and those depend largely on my physical environment, mental state, and the people i am surrounded with). I am usually pretty happy but can easily get bogged down by my anxiety which leads me to feel a bit overwhelmed. I think I am typically a go-with-the-flow type of person and won't usually try to control plans or impose my thoughts/ feelings into situations that involve other people. This is probably attributable to the fact that i'm pretty non-confrontational and don't like to start/ engage in conflict even when it might be necessary. I mostly enjoy activities that involve a small group of people like hiking or going to the beach so that I can be social but also have one on one time with people that I want to talk to more deeply. I am a little disorganized (both in my room and thoughts) but can focus on my tasks well under a time crunch or when they are very important. I can get really invested in conversations about things i am passionate about or find interesting, and one of my favorite things to do with other people is get down rabbit holes of random topics. When i'm bored, I like to spend my free time listening to music or doing creative activities like drawing and crocheting
negative_text: I deal a lot with anxiety which affects me both socially and individually. I think sometimes it is easy for me to get closed off when I feel anxious and get really overwhelmed by negative thoughts. I don't usually try to tackle this head on but rather usually just resort to using distractors to deal with anxiety. I think I also sometimes come off a little stand-offish because of the way I get nervous around other people which stops me from always being personable and easy to talk to.

text:
I am a pretty easy-going person. I don't like conflict and prefer to work out problems if there are any, and I can hold a conversation quite well. Despite this, I am very introverted by nature and do not like to socialize past a certain limit; I would call myself a "bubbly introvert" in that I can socialize well when needed to, but I still require my downtime. As such, I can also appear very quiet at times. 
I do tend to get emotional sometimes, but I usually keep those to myself and try not to bother people with my emotions. I can get depressed and anxious easily but I put in a lot of effort to try and not let it affect the people around me. As a student and as a worker I am very diligent and detail-oriented, and I can take care of a lot of things on my own. I am an artist, so creative freedom is important to me and I also like sharing my ideas with people who like to listen to stories.

My hobbies include digital art and playing video games. Being in a creative environment helps me relax, so I guess you can say I am a creative person! I like to work on my own projects by myself and then share them with others, however, I may also discuss ideas with very close friends when I feel like it. In terms of communication I am definitely more introverted; I don't realy feel the need to make small talk all the time but I can engage in it when the situation arises. When problems come up I do prefer direct communication to work out the problem as quickly as possible, and can get easily irritated if others don't do the same and the problem persists. I am very conflict-avoidant, which can also hinder my communication skills sometimes, and sometimes difficult conversations do make me extremely anxious. However, I do try to prepare myself as best as I can for those kinds of conversations so that my emotions dont' overwhelm me during the conversation.
negative_text: I do tend to have very depressive and anxious sides to me. I'm pretty sure I grew up with a lot of social anxiety, which really fueled depressive aspects of myself growing up as I had an extroverted mom and I would often be pushed into roles I hated. For some reason people also tend to default me as a leader in many cases, which did not help me with my anxiety. To be honest, my problem solving capabilities are pretty good and I am generally an ok/good leader, but I do not like to be one and prefer to stay as a background worker. I also have a hard time seeing my own merits which can make writing resumes and cover letters difficult as well, as I don't really know how to "sell" myself without feeling some sort of imposter syndrome. I really do try to make sure my own negative thought patterns dont' affect those around me, but I can get some pretty depressive thoughts regularly. There are days where I don't want to do anything and wish time would just stop so I wouldn't have to do anything, but my anxiety keeps me up and running because I then start to feel anxious when I haven't done anything. I'm working on it currently, and there has been quite a bit of progress thankfully, but I am still working on it.

text:
I spend periods of time alone, reading, absorbing, where my social battery is empty and I can find solace in solitude. Other time I itch for interaction and enjoy conversation that is quick with quips, bits, jokes. I would describe myself as conscientious, trying to be aware as I can of how my actions affect others. Annoyed when people interrupt, are too crass, don't look out for each other. I am never serious. Engaging with me means eating through layers of irony. If I don't like you, I wont speak. I think that's a negative trait about myself that I could work on. New people think I'm intensely quiet and reserved, maybe even stupid, but I often reach a point where I suddenly become comfortable being myself, not afraid of being rebuked. 

Other's find me meditative. Between banter I could become satisfied with sitting outside in stillness. Basking in the outside with no need to add anything to the sounds that already exist. I think that insecurity means that I search for validation in conversations and recognition, or even listening (I don't feel very listened to often). When I am listened to I think I can talk too much. Weave a conversation around myself, with myself as moderator and topic changer. I think that this is a remnant of covid society, where I had nobody to talk to for months. 

I am judgy towards people for various irrational reasons. This is something I need to fix but it feels like my unconscious mind picks apart any new person and labels them as unacceptable as soon as they reveal something not agreeable to me. Not that they aren't a good person but because I hold some sort of fallacy that I need to share the same music, habits, hobbies, as someone to be friends with them. My high school friends have shown that this isn't true. I think I have found that shared hobbies, music, are a proxy to a good friendship but not a requirement, necessarily.
negative_text:
I alluded to this at the end of my previous response, but I am often very judgemental or negative towards people if they don't align with some artbitrary value system that I somehow inherited. I am often convinced that I can't be friends with people who don't share every part of their hobbies or selves with me which isn't true at all.

I am also a downer sometimes. If my social battery runs out, if I'm tired, hungry, especially if I'm alread the center of attention, as I described in the previous part, I will bring the morale of an entire group down with me. Rather than accepting that I'm just down with social interaction, I will often convince myself that my friends dislike me and pick out their negative traits and tell myself something like "I shouldn't see these people again". I don't think I'm too self-righteous. I know there's a lot of things wrong with me, but I worry and know that I'm too critical of others. I'm often the one to cut off a friendship, end a relationship, cancel a date. And because of that I have few friends.

text: To my future roommate! My personality type is extroverted, intuitive, more feeling than thinking, and a planner rather than a procrastinator. Upon first meeting me, I might be more quiet, but as you get to know me I'm definitely more loud. I am a very perceptive person and if I know you well enough, will be able to pick out how you are feeling with just a glance. I tend to overshare, especially with strangers, but can also be closed off when it comes to describing my own thoughts and feelings. My favorite activities include doing anything that is outdoors, such as reading, drawing, doing crossword puzzles, and more. I love hanging out with my brother and my friends, whether we're just driving around in a car or taking a walk. I sometimes get into phases where I get fixated on starting a new project, such as learning how to make rings, or sew, and then eventually it tapers off. I am only consistent in some aspects of my life such as school and scheduled activities, but with my hobbies, my interests tend to drift. I can be anxious at times, especially if it is a close friend who is upset at me. I hate confrontation and being confronted, even though I know it can be beneficial. I am not that good at cooking but if there is a recipe I will follow it to a T. Timers make me anxious. People say that I am a people pleaser. I tend to prioritize my friendships over my relationships. I like to be reassured.
negative_text: I tend to like to do things in a way that I believe would be best. Since I am not that introspective, it can be hard for me to share about exactly what I am feeling because I sometimes do not even know what I feel. I am very indecisive so if someone wants a decision made, I might not be the best person to ask, especially if it is under pressure. I am a perfectionist when it comes to projects and sometimes take on more than others so I can personally do the assignment/project.

text: I would describe myself as a cheerful and bubbly person. This cheerful and bubbly rings true especially when you first meet me. I think after I while I tend to mellow out and become a more quiet version of myself. I am more of a reactive person and I am pretty emotional, I like being able to feel my feelings. I am pretty understanding and empathetic, as I love seeing things from the other person's point of view even if it opposes my own. I am efficient and love being timely. I like being organized and believe that most things have their own place. I enjoy listening rather than being heard by others unless I am really close to you. if so, then I will also share my own life and experiences in a deeper manner. I love helping other people in whatever aspect that I am, and sometimes it will drain me so I am learning to step back and only say yes to those who I can help without losing time for myself. I am more reserved and would label myself as an extroverted introvert, meaning that being around big groups of people drains me. I would say that I lean on the quiet side of the scale and enjoy having time that is peaceful and restful. I like spending time with other people, but I also don't mind spending time with myself. Enjoying spending time with myself has definitely been something that I've had to learn over the years. I think long showers and grocery shopping can be considered herapy and really enjoy it.
negative_text: I can get frustrated easily over smaller tasks or comments, however, these also tend to fade quickly. When I get stressed out over school or just over life in general, I tend to ice people out because I have trouble asking for help. Not saying the right things when I am stressed out can cause me to get irritated. I can be stubborn when it comes to doing something that I really want to do. I am not the most adventurous and spontaneous person out there and I like routine. I am not the best at confrontation so if you do something I have an issue with then I will most likely not say anything for a while and let it build up.

text: I am a respectful and enthusiastic person and my fatal flaw is always wanting to put my all into everything I do. When I am in the zone I am single-minded about what I'm doing, so watch out because I can get cranky and frustrated when I really like something and it doesn't work out the way I want it too. I am insistent about boundaries and communication so you have to be receptive and ready to learn if you do not already know how to communicate your emotions. I am mentally ill, so communication is a daily necessity for me and I cannot be in a close relationship if the person does not know how to communicate. If you do not know how to communicate, you put me in danger of daily emotional burnout and stress because I do not have the most stable emotions. I hate judgemental people because one day we are all going to die and nothing we say or do matters that much, and being that negative towards someone just because you don't like what they are is stupid and frustrating. I try to take full responsibility for my actions and I understand that just because something upset me doesn't mean that the other person intended for it to be that way. I try to deal with my frustration, anger, and sadness when it happens and not push it back, so that I can reapproach the situation with a stable and nonreactionary perspective. I want to make the world a better place but I often get overwhelmed with how to start, so I really value others' opinions on big world questions so I can make sense of the world around me. I love talking about philosophical topics and questioning the nature of the world around me, which is fun sometimes but other times it can feel overwhelming to consider so many large things at once. I am trying to teach myself to live in the moment, but it is hard.
negative_text: I don't believe in hiding the worst parts of yourself because I did that for the first 19 years of my life and it almost killed me. However, obviously, you don't start out saying the absolute worst things about yourself. My fatal flaw, as I mentioned before, is always wanting to commit 100%. When I hit a wall, as one can often do with school or with social life, I get sad, mad, and frustrated all at once. It is hard to share my emotions with others because I grew up with a mental illness that was mostly ignored and pushed aside by the people around me. I know that my emotions are often irrational, but I never had an emotional support system that would comfort me through these irrational thoughts and fears so I always thought I was crazy so I also ignored and minimized my own fears. It has gotten to the point that the only time I display anxious behaviors (shaking, grabbing hands, eyes moving) is when I'm on the verge of a panic attack because I am so used to suppressing my own anxiety. However, I am learning to comfort and take care of myself, and when I start feeling uncomfortable and I don't know why I make sure to slow down, find a safe space, and think out what I should do about it rather than just suppressing it until I cry from stress. :D yay me!

text: Hi, I'm Patricia and here's a little bit about myself! I'm a pretty hardworker when it comes to school and hobbies, but generally, I'm pretty lazy. Haha, I think I only work hard in school so that I can be lazy in the future. Work hard now and hopefully reap the benefits in the future! I also care a lot about my friends and would say that I try to be empathetic. I also love a good laugh, so I would say I'm pretty lighthearted most of the time and carefree. Don't get me wrong, I'm also kinda anxious sometimes and can often talk myself into hypothetical situations that aren't very likely and then just stress out about it. I think I also try my best to still be accepting of everything that happens even if it doesn't go the way I specifically want. I try to be optimistic about others but tend to be quite pessimistic about myself just because I've always been taught to assume the worst but hope for the best, but I fear I have taken it one level too far but just fixating on the worst. If I were to be in one state for the rest of my life, I would love to be at peace, it's something I yearn for and something that is so rare in this world. Anyways, I think I also like to embrace my childish side, so I like to have fun, be weird, and just ignore what the world thinks of me because at the end of the day, I'm still gonna be a hardworker and I believe that my work will speak louder than what others think of me, so I will just be myself, have fun, (of course, still be respectful to others), and just try not to lose myself to the world. I'm always down to have more friendships with other people and I can't wait to meet you and get to know you! I pride myself on wearing my heart on my sleeve, so I hope that you accept my unfiltered personality. Again, don't worry, I will always try to consider my actions if it makes you uncomfortable, but I'll definitely spring a deep philosophical question on you, like "do you think joy or happiness is better?" and something dumb like "would you rather be able to teleport but only vertically, or be able to fly, but only 10 feet off the ground?". Excited to meet ya!
negative_text: I've noticed that when I am in a bad mood, I tend to do really bad at being empathetic. It's difficult for me to both share joys and share sorrows with others when I myself am sad or angry because I try so hard to repress my emotions, that it also affects how well I can share emotions. On that note, I think my repressing defense mechanism can sometimes cause me to feel resentment. I try so hard to make sure to remove all negative feelings I have towards others or things that annoy me by repressing them. While this works in the short term, it can often build up over time since I don't let it out. I just don't want to be unhappy at others, so I push it aside. I'm working on it, but it's definitely something I struggle with. I also am quite a jealous person when it comes to career. I think it's because my self-worth primarily comes from my accomplishments since I've got nothing else going for me that I believe I should be proud of (since I think I'm below average in almost everything else), so when I come across someone who is average or above average in most things and are better at me in career-related things, I feel very attacked because I end up feeling worthless because who would ever want someone who is worse than another in every aspect. I am quite defensive about my career and it can definitely lead to some toxicity sometimes. As a result, just like I repress my emotions and try to not deal with it, I also do that with my friends who I feel threatened by. I still try to be their friend, but I try to minimize interactions so that I won't feel jealous.

text:
I would say that I am very outgoing, I love meeting new people and hearing their stories. I like to meet people from different groups. Historically I have been involved in groups with a lot of different interests. In high school I did cross country, and singing and in college most of my friends I met through my dorm, Chinese class, the cross country team, my a cappella group, the Stoicism club I ran or the meditation group I was a part of. That is how I like to roll, make friends from many different groups, I find it provides a sense of balance in my life. I would say that friends are the most important thing in my life. I care about finding community, and typically that manifests in engaging in meaningful activities with other people. A running group is a good example of that, several of my close friends have come from the cross country teams I have been on. 
Other than being outgoing and enjoying connecting with people, I really enjoy cooking and meditating. Those are two big aspects of my personality. I love to cook and eat, it provides a form of flow and exploration in my day. I would say I am a relatively mindful person, I respond to situations with equanimity and don't dwell on things too much. Other things about me include my love and appreciation for meditation--specifically Vipassana meditation. I love playing video games. In general I love almost all entertainment mediums. I love listening to music. When no one is around, I quite honestly dance like no one is watching--because no one is. I love to blast music on the TV and just groove around the apartment. I am someone who enjoys expressing my body. While I haven't fully figured out my sexuality, I am certainly queer. text:
I guess the first thing someone should know about me is that I'm incredibly adaptable and flexible. I love embracing new experiences and am always eager to shake things up. If my roommate wants to spontaneously rearrange our furniture at 3 a.m. or take a spur-of-the-moment trip to a quirky small town, I'm their guy. I thrive on keeping life fresh and fun.

I'm also a total extrovert who gets my energy from being around people, probably because I grew up in a joint family in India. Nothing makes me happier than a living room full of old and new friends laughing until we can barely breathe. So, my roommate should be okay with me if I'm constantly inviting folks over for game nights or striking up conversations with everyone we meet. People are just endlessly fascinating to me.

One of my greatest strengths is my ability to empathize and attune to others' emotions. If my roommate is stressing over a looming deadline or ecstatic about acing that presentation, I'll be right there with them, feeling all the feels. I just inherently pick up on people's vibes, and I care deeply. My roommates can always count on me as their rock and biggest cheerleader.

I am also very curious and appreciate the incredible diversity of human cultures. I'm that person who constantly peppers people with questions about their family traditions, pleading with friends to teach me words in their native languages, and attempting to cook dishes from every corner of the globe. So, I'll be thrilled to learn about my roommate's cultural background and experience!

So yeah, that's me in a nutshell—a fun-loving, ultra-extroverted, endlessly adaptable culture vulture who can't wait to build an incredible friendship with my new roommate. I just know we're going to have the best time learning and growing together.
negative_text:
I can be prone to bouts of self-doubt, insecurity, and comparing myself unfavorably to others. I tend to take things too personally, and I am sensitive. As an extrovert, I sometimes overextend myself in social settings and feel depleted afterward.
I get impatient and frustrated when things move slowly, and I can be conflict-averse, bottling up anger and disappointment. People-pleasing tendencies lead me to overcommit and have trouble saying no.

While I'm generally upbeat, I have my share of flaws, neuroses, and challenging emotions to contend with. Like all other human beings on this planet, I'm a WIP, learning to navigate my quirks and rough edges with humility and self-compassion.

text: I think that my personality is highly attributed to my adhd and anxiety.  I am often described as weird, bubbly, naive, self deprecating, and funny. My favorite activities are ones where I am able to be on the go or working towards some kind of objective.  I love skiing, running, kayaking, skating, biking and crocheting and playing boardgames and videogames with my friends.  I think that I have a very nurturing personality as well.  I love to host people and to cook for people.  I also am someone who needs a lot of reassurance and quiet time.  Since I overthink so much it helps me to know that I am doing the right thing or even if I am doing the wrong thing.  overall, I like to make small things in my life special and fun but oftentimes, this ends in me feeling hurt because I care so much about external people and things around me.  I am also someone who is perpetually late but I am a hypocrite cause I hate waiting.
negative_text: Something that is difficult for me to talk to others about myself is that I have a lot of separation anxiety and difficulty to "stay connected while being separated".  The most difficult parts about myself are that I have the tendency to be anxious and controlling when I feel uncertain or like I have little control over a situation or aspect of my life.  This is especially present in my romantic and close relationships.  There are a lot of times where things that should be fairly simple and easy for others are extremely difficult to me and I tend to latch on loved ones for support.  This leads to me creating a space where I am spreading a person thin or asking for a lot of emotional support that they may or may not have.  Its is an extremely vicious cycle because I end up overthinking more and feeling more and more anxious.

text:
Hey future roommate!

I’m really excited about moving in together and thought I’d share a bit about myself to help us get to know each other better. First off, I’d describe myself as a pretty easygoing person. I’m laid-back and open-minded, and I find it easy to get along with different kinds of people. One thing you should know is that I’m quite organized and I actually enjoy deep cleaning the house. It’s one of my stress-coping mechanisms, so you can count on the place being clean and tidy. If you’re ever busy or stressed, don’t worry – cleanliness won’t be an issue! In my free time, I love to dance. It’s a fun way for me to unwind and get some exercise. If you ever hear music playing and some commotion, it’s probably just me dancing around. However, if it ever bothers you, please don’t hesitate to let me know and I’ll be happy to stop or turn it down. I really value a healthy balance between having my own independence and being social. I enjoy spending time with others and making new friends, but I also appreciate having my own space and respect others’ need for privacy too. Cooking is another one of my favorite hobbies. I have an endless amount of recipe books, and I love choosing a new recipe each week to try out. I think it could be a great bonding activity for us if you’re interested in cooking together. It’s always fun to experiment with new dishes and share a meal.

Looking forward to meeting you and creating a comfortable living environment together. See you soon!
negative_text: Sometimes I can be a really independent person, and I truly value my alone time. While I do enjoy socializing and spending time with others, I often need a significant amount of solitude to recharge and maintain my balance. This independent streak can sometimes be seen as a negative trait. People might assume that I’m not putting enough effort into social situations or that I’m being distant. There are times when my need for independence might come across as me ignoring someone or not including them in my daily activities. It’s not intentional; it’s just how I manage my mental and emotional well-being. I know this can be challenging, especially in a shared living situation, and I’m aware that it might make others feel excluded or unimportant. I try to be mindful of this and make an effort to communicate openly about my need for space, but it’s something that can occasionally cause misunderstandings. Despite this, I genuinely value good relationships and am always willing to discuss and find a balance that works for everyone involved.

text: On the outside, I think I am someone that can be "super on" or "super off", in that, I can either be really social and outgoing, or really passive and reserved. However, once the ice gets broken, and I get closer with someone, I tend to become more social with them more often than not. Although, there are definitely times where I need time and (physical and mental) space to myself, away from any form of socializing. In terms of feelings and expression of those feelings, I naturally wear my emotions on my sleeves (for better or for worse), but I am always conscious of how these expressions may come off as super overwhelming and aggressive, so I try to tone down the degree and intensity in which I express myself emotionally. I also believe that I am a "personality chameleon", as I tend to try and blend in with the social group I am with, which can sometimes differ heavily from my personality with another social group. This also goes for interests I may have and things I like to do in my free time, as I generally have some form of interest in a very large and broad variety of things.

text:
I'm quite introverted. I'm not sure if that's always been the case—There have been periods of my life, especially in adolescence, where I seemed to really revel in social interaction and experiences. Since going to college, those feelings have significantly waned. 

I do not particularly seek out novel experiences. I enjoy keeping a small, close circle of acquaintances rather than a larger, more superficial one. And I've noticed that I am quite sensitive to outside stimuli: I enjoy the countryside to the city, a quiet night in to a "fun", active night out. 

I get anxious in certain situations. Public speaking, for one. If I feel out of place at a social event and am feeling particularly self-conscious that day, I find myself anxious. I also am quite the germaphobe so most things germ-related (like having to touch a very public door knob) gives me considerable anxiety compared to the average person. 

I really value human connection and my own self growth. I often think about my relationship with my family and friends and what I can do to be better to them. (I do really want to be better, but that doesn't always translate into direct results—but I am working on it!) 

 I am not particularly high energy. I enjoy quiet, lazy activities. I'm curious and love learning new things.
negative_text:
One of the biggest aspects of my personality that seems to most negatively affect others is my neuroticism around germs. I've held this anxiety for as long as I can remember. If I feel comfortable enough, I can be very controlling and domineering in the way I enforce germ-related rules like making someone take off their shoes, wash their hands, etc. 

I can also be moody, especially around my family. However, I find my mood/energy to be much more stable around friends/strangers. 


I can also be judgmental in the way that I see others and the world. I am working on this, but I do observe feelings of irritation or disgust in situations when I know, rationally, I should be more understanding and compassionate (like a mother dealing with their crying baby on a plane).

text:
Hi! My name is Gaurav and I am a junior here at UC Berkeley studying Environmental Economics and Policy and Psychology. I'll start with everything I feel is relevant to you as a future roommate, and then I will get into other facets of my personality with any extra time that I have. For starters, I am pretty clean and when I do get messy I make sure it is contained to my room. I am used to living with other people, having lived in a triple freshman year and a fraternity my sophomore year. I now live with two of my friends where we each have singles. Both my housemates are girls, which though not technically implying anything, might be interesting/useful for some people to know. Anyways, a chief complaint of every person I have lived with is that I am not often home. I am pretty involved with extracurriculars and I go out to see my friends. Unfortunately, that means I spend the least time at home outside of sleeping and eating. That in no way doesn't mean I don't enjoy the company of the people I live with, I just like getting out of the house. Other than that some other relevant things include that I have a car. I am pretty flexible in letting others use it so long as you ask me first and fill up the gas. Also I would say I go out a good amount, probably every weekend. I think it is nice when my friends have company over/kickback or small party environments. 

Now in the remaining few minutes let me try and get into my personality. I am slightly hesitant to completely write uninhibited as this is for a class, but I also don't really care that much and this feels more like a journal entry. I'm imperfect that is for sure, many of my friend's have told me I need to learn to better advocate for myself – something I have spent a lot of time thinking about and currently work on. With the minute I have left, I really like being outdoors (rock climbing, surfing, hiking, or laying in the grass), going to museums or long photo walks, being with the people I love and animals! By no means do I already do this, but my goal is always to lead with kindness first. Being patient, gentle, thoughtful, considerate, and genuine are all qualities I try and embody and value highly.

With that comes feelings of inadequacy, loneliness, and general negativity. Recognizing the power of our internal dialogue I have been trying to incorporate mindfulness, and specifically metta mediation in my life. But to get into the negatives, I would say I have pretty low self confidence sometimes which can lead me to spiral into a disillusioned state and pessimistic view of the world. Additionally, I overbook myself often and feel pretty overwhelmed sometimes. I always consistently feel like I am not good enough. I really am trying to work on all these things and truly believe I can control how I feel about myself and the compassion I can develop and work on for myself so I have no hesitation to share these aspects of myself, but I refuse to let them define me. I can always try and be better.

I overload myself oftentimes and don't feel super confident about my direction in life? I'm applying to many things that sound interesting to me, and whatever accepts me will determine my future path. So I feel a large amount of uncertainty.

text: I would describe my personality as primarily kind. I really do care about the well-being and happiness of others. Sometimes I think I care too much and it gets in the way of my own happiness. I try to be funny and I also try to treat people how I would like to be treated. I'm intelligent in a variety of areas and have a large amount of emotional intelligence. I am very self-aware and can always tell why I feel a certain way. I like to listen to others and have meaningful conversations. I like to think of myself as really open-minded and understanding.
negative_text: I would say one of the more negative aspects of my personality that I touched on previously was the fact that I sometimes care too much about other people's happiness and feelings and that gets in the way of my own happiness because I get so wrapped up in how other people feel that I get left feeling defeated and depleted. I also sometimes am quick to anger although I try not to let things get to me. It feels like a lot of things make me upset so I'm trying to work on being calmer. I think I am too sensitive although that's not necessarily a bad thing.

text: Caring, organized, driven, ambitious, outgoing, friendly, selfless, talkative, passionate, open-minded, approachable, reliable
negative_text: anxious, insecure, moody, pessimistic, irritable, stubborn, vengeful

text: I am an introverted person that can easily be outgoing and extroverted if needed. I love my family and my friends. I enjoy my alone time, but I don't like being alone always. I am very outspoken and direct. I enjoy listening to other's opinions, and I'm fine with disagreements. I handle arguments well, and I do try to avoid conflict. I am not easily offended, and I assume the best in people's intentions rather than the worst. I enjoy self-deprecating humor, and I like to find the upside or funny thing in everything. I am very artistic, and I like being creative. I don't go overboard to be unique, but I like that I am firm in my beliefs. I express my feelings easily, and I have no problem speaking what's on my mind. I prefer to be happy rather than sad, so I do manipulate my own head a bit to keep myself happy if sad things happen. I think it's not about repressing emotions because I do let myself be sad, but being weighed down by sadness and negative emotions is just a very slow and not great way to live. Things are better when you're happy and enjoying the life around you. I have some anxiety from time to time, but that's usually well managed with healthy coping mechanisms. I have attention issues, and I do try to correct them. I am a very open person, and I will talk openly about pretty much anything and everything going on with me feelings-wise or just in my daily life. I have chronic pain issues, but I strive to not let it affect my life in an impactful way, and I enjoy making fun of myself instead of wallowing in self-pity. Looking at the upside is much better. I am very confident in myself, and I like that I have good self-confidence.
negative_text: I struggle with time management, and I have come to accept this rather than making strives to fix it as I have in the past. My psychologist was not helpful with this issue, and while I have tried almost everything under the sun to fix it and have made improvements, it's not great yet. I have motivation issues, and I do try to fix this as well, and I haven't given up yet. I have social anxiety in certain situations, specifically "parties" like frat parties, and I do try to fix this, but it always lingers. It's fine though, I never really found that kind of thing to be essential to being happy, and I enjoy other group activities much more. I am not great at "maintaining relationships" in that I won't reach out to someone over text or etc that often if I'm no longer seeing them face to face often. However, I still love my friends, so when I do see them again, everything is good. That kind of communication is hard for me, but I do need to get better at it. I think that is linked to my motivational issues, and so when one gets better, the other might too.

text: I would say I am a very contradictory person. Most of the time, I am quite introverted in front of crowds, trying to hide myself at the corner and not being spotted. However, as long as we get familiar with each other, I will be very talkative and willing to share things with people, I am an outgoing and easygoing girl to some extent. If you would like to know me in brief, I am a typical INFP-type person who loves thinking about some random things that might pop up in my mind during conversations. I have a whole list of things I love that sparkled in my mind before, such as "the sound when stepping on fallen leaves," etc. I am sentimental sometimes, always being affected by the weather. I will try to find a "perfect" atmosphere in my place to optimize my personal mental state and emotional feeling! I am very easy to get along with and try to read the air in most situations. I am really bad at any kind of sports but love walking in the evening after dinner to feel the breeze and spend a short period with myself alone. This is the most common way I use to recharge myself. Listening to music is another way because I always believe there is a very personal story behind each song, so I really enjoy finding these stories through flows and lyrics. I like K-pop and my idol also acts as my emotional support for most of the time. Nice to meet you!
negative_text: As I mentioned before, I am easily influenced by external factors, such as the weather, people's comments, and even tomorrow's schedule as well. So I sometimes become not very tempered only because of a rainy day and will be really tired of doing anything. It is really hard to visualize this, but I do believe there is a "vibe", "atmosphere", or "setting" that affects my emotions a lot. Also, I can be very sensitive sometimes. Being too careful makes me pay too much attention to others' comments and words, which hugely affects my days sometimes only due to one word I do not like. It also makes me form a comparatively negative impression on this person and this one may not even do that intentionally. Also, if I spend too much time on socializing with new people, I will be tired quickly and would not like to talk or meet anyone in short period.

text: My ethnicity is Filipino, Mexican, Native, and supposedly a little Irish, Armenian, and Hawaiian, but culturally, I would say I have cultural traits of San Fransisco Latinos but many generations worth of being in the US. My family has been here in the States for several generations in the Bay Area and Bay Area culture, traits, and lifestyle is ingrained into my behaviorisms. I would describe my personality as Myers-Briggs ENFP-T and Enneagram 2. I am concerned with concepts and deeper meanings, philosophy and psychology, life, spirituality, and faith. I am an artist and a musician. I am the type of person who is very particular in terms of what I want because I tend to think of endless possibilities in my mind and choose the best one. I really love learning about various topics and am very conversational. I love to challenge myself to see different points of views, perspectives, and ways of viewing the world. My core values are honesty, truth, and love, and I honestly try to represent those values in my behavior. However, with past traumas, toxic traits, and my developing person, I can stray away from the person I aspire to be. However, at the end of the day, I typically end up going back to the path where I try to be the best me I can be...because I believe in life, what matters is the effort to reach the goal, not the goal being reached. I try to keep myself focused on the goal of being the best me I can be knowing I may not reach it in my life.
negative_text: At my worst, I am selfish, prideful, arrogant, entitled, self-centered, emotionally detached, and morally bereft. Another worst version of me (probably related to seasonal depression) is numb, dark, low-energy, having no goals, aspirations, dreams, visions, or directions in life. I can also get into states where I have extreme low self view, extreme worry, anxiety, and fear. When I am angry, I break my character and easily consider breaking the morals I previously considered not to break at all costs.

text: Hi! My name is Zoe. I am a senior transfer who will be rooming with you for the upcoming year. I am a pretty neat person and I prefer to have some boundaries. Some basic rules I would like is to respect each others privacy and belongings and to not go through them. Another is to not bring friends over until you've mentioned it to everyone rooming with us. One thing you should know is that I tend to get tired of socializing pretty quickly so if I seem disinterested I hope you know I am not trying to be rude or trying to ignore you. I just need space to regain energy. I like to sleep early on weekdays that I have school and later on days that I don't. Another thing is that I really hate spiders so if you hear me scream it's probably because I have spotted one. I also am allergic to cats so let me know if you have one ahead of time. I don't really cook but I might try to learn some simple healthy recipes.
negative_text: Some negative parts of my personality is that I tend to get grumpier the more tired or hungry I am. Another is that I don't like noise so I would probably keep asking it to be quiet. I also tend to hold grudges even though I try not to. An example of this is once I fought with my sister and refused to talk to her. This lasted for about 2-3 weeks and would have gone on longer but I decided to forgive her since it was her birthday. Otherwise I would have kept ignoring her.

text: I am considerate and generous towards those close to me. I believe I am up-front about my opinions, beliefs, and values, and I greatly value those who extend the same courtesy. I am mindful of other people's space and feelings and do my best to make sure others feel respected and heard. I am relatively introverted, though I am very talkative and enjoy making jokes around my close friends. As a more reserved individual, I enjoy spending time in my house; I like to crochet, read, and journal.
negative_text: I am an anxious person; I tend to assume the worst about vague situations, especially romantic ones. I often need reassurance from my partner due to these anxious tendencies. I have a hard time forgiving people for any slights they've made against me; sometimes I hold grudges, or refuse to communicate why their actions have upset me. I experience random bouts of extreme self-criticism, usually after a perceived failure or mistake. I am unable to tolerate making mistakes or not knowing things I find self-explanatory.
